{"title_page": "Bishop Auckland railway station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Railway station in County Durham, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = Bishop Auckland\n| code         = BIA\n| image_name   = Bishop Auckland Railway Station.jpg\n| manager      = [[Northern Trains]]\n| locale       = [[Bishop Auckland]]\n| borough      = [[County Durham]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|54.6573|-1.6778|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| platforms    = 2\n<!-- | lowusage0405 = 66,681\n| lowusage0506 = {{increase}} 74,092\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 85,063\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 94,785\n| lowusage0809 = {{increase}} 96,712\n| lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 95,428\n| lowusage1011 = {{decrease}} 94,732\n| usage1112 = {{increase}} 0.101\n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.102\n| usage1314 = {{increase}} 0.109 -->\n| usage1415 = {{decrease}} 0.108\n| usage1516 = {{increase}} 0.110\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.119\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.123\n| usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.155\n| caption      = \n| owner        = \n| gridref      = NZ208291\n| original     = [[Weardale Railway|Bishop Auckland and Weardale Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n| years        = 8 November 1843\n| events       = Station opened\n| dft_category = F1\n}}\n[[File:Bishop Auckland 2 railway station1805267 f99ac746.jpg|thumb|275px|right|View westward along the main platform in 1965, providing services to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}}, and {{stnlnk|Consett}} via {{stnlnk|Crook}}]]\n[[File:Bishop Auckland 1 railway station1805295 9d064167.jpg|thumb|275px|right|View along the curved platforms in 1965, which served the former [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|NER]] line to {{stnlnk|Durham}}, and [[Clarence Railway]] via {{stnlnk|Byers Green}}]]\n[[File:Wearhead station geograph-2354909-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|275px|right|The last scheduled passenger train to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}} waits to leave Bishop Auckland on 27 June 1953, headed by ex-[[NER Class C1]] No. 65078]]\n'''Bishop Auckland railway station''' serves the town of [[Bishop Auckland]] in [[County Durham]], England. The station is the western terminus of the [[Tees Valley Line]] (also referred to as the Bishop Line West of {{stnlnk|Darlington}}) {{convert|12|mi|km}} north of Darlington.\n\nWhen it is operating, a connection can be made with the [[Weardale Railway|Weardale Heritage Railway]] at the nearby '''Bishop Auckland West railway station''' for trains towards {{stnlnk|Stanhope}}.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/timetables|title=Weardale Railway - Timetables|website=The Weardale Railway Trust|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBishop Auckland gained its first rail link in 1842,<ref>{{harvnb|Body|1988|p=43}}</ref> when the [[Stockton and Darlington Railway|Stockton and Darlington Railway (S&DR)]] backed [[Weardale Railway|Bishop Auckland and Weardale Railway (BA&WR)]] gained the powers via an [[Act of Parliament]] to build a railway line from the S&DR's station at {{stnlnk|Shildon}} via Bishop Auckland and [[Witton-le-Wear]] into [[Crook, County Durham]].<ref name=ButtP35>{{harvnb|Butt|1995|p=35}}</ref>\n\nThe company initially built a temporary terminus at [[South Church railway station|South Church]], which opened on 19 April 1842. A road coach service then extended the service into Bishop Auckland, and a secondary road coach service also ran to [[Rainton Meadows]]. After completion of the Shildon tunnel, the BA&WR erected a permanent station on the current site, which opened to freight on 8 November 1843, and passengers on 30 January 1843.<ref name=ButtP35/> All operations were sub-leased as agreed to the S&DR.<ref name=ButtP35/>\n\nIn 1844, after the [[West Durham Railway]] extended from a junction with the [[Clarence Railway]] at {{stnlnk|Byers Green}} to Crook, the S&DR extended the BA&WR from Bishop Auckland along the river valley to [[Witton-le-Wear]], and then into {{rws|Crook}}. In 1845, the S&DR came to an agreement with the [[Derwent Iron Company]] to sub-lease the southern section of the former [[Stanhope and Tyne Railway]]. It extended the line from Crook to {{stnlnk|Waskerley}} and then to [[Blackhill, Consett|Blackhill]], and it was opened as the [[Weardale Extension Railway|Weardale Extension Railway (WXR)]].<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nIn July 1845 Parliament passed the Wear Valley Act, which allowed the extension of the BA&WR from a junction at Witton-le-Wear to {{stnlnk|Frosterley}}, and a small branch line across the river to [[Bishopley]]. With all works again undertaken by the S&DR, this line opened on 3 August 1847. After these works had been completed, the BA&WR amalgamated with the WXR. All service were operated by the S&DR, which officially took over the new company in January 1857.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nOn 1 April 1857, the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway (NER)]] started a service from {{stnlnk|Durham}} to Bishop Auckland at a new terminus in Tenter Street. However, the S&DR and NER quickly came to the agreement of development of a joint station in the town, and so rebuilt the existing former BA&WR station, with NER trains using it from December 1857.<ref name=\"ButtP35\"/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nIn 1862, an Act of Parliament was passed allowing the S&DR backed [[Frosterley and Stanhope Railway]] to extend the line to {{stnlnk|Stanhope}}, thus allowing trains to transport [[limestone]] from the Newlandside Estate on the south side of the town. This brought about the extension of the [[South Durham and Lancashire Union Railway]] from {{stnlnk|Barnard Castle}} into Bishop Auckland in 1862, and with the final addition of traffic from an extension of the [[Clarence Railway]] at {{stnlnk|Byers Green}}, eventually resulted in the NER rebuilding the station again in December 1867.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nThe final extension of the Weardale Railway to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}} opened on 21 October 1895, with the NER having resited the station at {{stnlnk|Stanhope}} to provide a more suitable gradient for the heavy limestone trains. Between Eastgate and Westgate at Cambo Keels, sidings were established to serve the Weardale Iron Company's Heights limestone quarry, which is still in operation today. This final extension of the Weardale Railway bought about the final and largest layout of Bishop Auckland railway station, which was now rebuilt in triangular form with four platforms in 1905.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>  Only three of these were normally used for passenger trains, with platform 1 handing trains towards Crook & Wearhead and platforms 2 & 3 dealing with services on the Barnard Castle, Ferryhill & Durham lines.  Platform 4 (on the chord linking the Durham & Crook lines) was mostly used for parcels & newspaper traffic and for racing pigeon specials.\n\nAs elsewhere the UK, rail traffic in the area declined after [[World War II]], with the Wearhead branch the first to lose its passenger trains in 1953. The principal closures came in the 1960s mainly as a result of the [[Beeching Axe]], with services to: Barnard Castle via [[West Auckland]] ending in June 1962; Durham in May 1964;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/bishop_auckland/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations: Bishop Auckland Station|website=www.disused-stations.org.uk}}</ref> and Crook in March 1965. This left only the former original S&DR line to {{stnlnk|Darlington}} line in operation, along with the freight-only branch traffic to [[Eastgate, County Durham|Eastgate]].<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nThe station remained more or less intact (although increasingly forlorn and run-down) for more than 20 years thereafter, though by the early 1980s only the former platform 3 was in use<ref name=DisBisAuk/> (along with the former Bishop Auckland East signal box).  It was eventually replaced by the current structure on 6 June 1986. This stands on the site of the former Crook branch platform, on a siding off the now single 'main' line which continues on towards Stanhope & Eastgate. The signal box was abolished at the same time, with neighbouring Shildon box assuming control of the much-simplified layout.\n\nThe remaining station buildings were then demolished and the site sold off for retail redevelopment. The former goods yard is now a supermarket with carpark, and the Durham platform is now the site of a cycling and motoring store and a bank.<ref name=DisBisAuk>{{cite web |url= http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/bishop_auckland/index10.shtml |title=Bishop Auckland |publisher=Disused Stations |date=2 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe station is currently operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]], which provides [[National Rail]] passenger services. In 2012, Bishop Trains adopted the station from [[Northern Rail (Serco-Abellio)|Northern Rail]] (the operator at the time), providing a National Rail Ticket Office and staff for the station. Bishop Trains have further developed the Ticket Office and now provide a booking service for coach trips and holidays, and more recently, rail charters.  It is staffed six days per week throughout the year (Monday to Saturday 06:50-16:15).  At all other times, tickets must be purchased in advance or on the train.  Service running information is offered by timetable posters and Bishop Trains staff (when open).  Step-free access is available from the main entrance to the ticket office and platform.<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/BIA/details.html Bishop Auckland station facilities] ''National Rail Enquiries''; Retrieved 16 February 2017</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the station was revamped. In the former toilet block, a glass front waiting room was constructed, alongside a new toilet and office.  Digital CIS displays have also been installed, as part of a scheme to provide these at all stations in the area (bar those at {{rws|Teesside Airport}} and {{rws|British Steel Redcar}}, which both have only a limited timetable).<ref>[http://www.necoastliners.co.uk/report-of-meeting-with-steve-payne-tees-valley-unlimited/ \"Report of meeting with Steve Payne, Tees Valley Unlimited\"] ''North East Coastliners'' news article 29 June 2015; Retrieved 17 February 2017</ref>\n\n===Station masters===\n{{Div col}}\n*William Crawford 1843 - 1886<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Death of and old Auckland resident |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000159/18861210/013/0003 |newspaper=Daily Gazette for Middlesbrough |location=England |date=10 December 1886 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> \n*William Boyne ???? - 1895\n*Matthew William Seymour 1895 - 1907<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.E.R. Appointments |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000726/19071214/112/0006  |newspaper=Newcastle Evening Chronicle |location=England |date=14 December 1907 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Darlington)\n*Robert Cocks 1908 - 1920<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Blyth man retiring |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002842/19201028/072/0003  |newspaper=Blyth News |location=England |date=28 October 1920 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref>  (formerly station master at Monkwearouth)\n*J.C. Pigg  1920 - 1921 (afterwards station master at Durham)\n*J.R. Winter 1922<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.E.R. Appointments |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001634/19220503/038/0002  |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Chronicle |location=England |date=3 May 1922 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> - ????\n*A. Howe 1934 - ????\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Services==\n{{Northern (train operating company) route 3}}\nTrains depart southbound to Darlington, {{stnlnk|Middlesbrough}} and {{stnlnk|Saltburn}} every hour through the day Monday to Saturday (with an additional p.m peak service).  This is an improvement from the two-hourly off-peak frequency formerly in place prior to the December 2017 timetable change.\nThe Sunday service is also now hourly until 20:00 since the timetable change in May 2018.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2018|44}}</ref>\n\n==Bishop Auckland West==\nThe [[Weardale Railway]] has built a separate platform, called '''Bishop Auckland West''', about {{convert|110|yd|m}} west of the National Rail station, from which regular passenger services to {{stnlnk|Stanhope}} initially operated from May 2010 until the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/news_2010.htm|title=Weardale Railway News 2010|access-date=4 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723070047/http://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/news_2010.htm|archive-date=23 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, the Weardale Railway Trust has operated passenger trains on selected weekdays and weekends for mostly tourist traffic using a [[British Rail Class 122|class 122 \"Bubble Car\"]]. Initially, this only ran between {{rws|Wolsingham}} and {{rws|Stanhope}} but, on 27 March 2016, this service was extended to {{rws|Witton-le-Wear}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/14386710.Trains_stop_in_County_Durham_village_for_first_time_in_50_years/|title=Trains stop in County Durham village for first time in 50 years {{!}} The Northern Echo|last=Russell|first=Helen|date=27 March 2016|website=The Northern Echo|access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref> and, after works were carried out by the Weardale Railway Trust to lift a short section of track at Broken Banks (approximately 1/2 mile west of Bishop Auckland station) to enable the embankment to be repaired (subsidence had made the line unusable for passenger traffic for a number of years prior to the works being carried out),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/16145275.Weardale_Railway_to_extend_service_to_Bishop_Auckland/|title=Weardale Railway to extend service to Bishop Auckland {{!}} The Northern Echo|last=Conner-Hill|first=Rachel|date=9 April 2018|website=The Northern Echo|access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> since July 2018, two of the three daily return services between Stanhope and Witton-le-Wear have been extended to Bishop Auckland West station.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Body |first=G. |year=1988 |title=PSL Field Guides - Railways of the Eastern Region Volume 2 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Wellingborough |isbn=1-85260-072-1 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page= |pages= |chapter= |quote= |ref=harv }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.ba-rail.co.uk Bishop Trains - Bishop Auckland]\n*[http://www.sdryt.org.uk Railway Youth Team - Bishop Auckland]\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Shildon|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Tees Valley Line]]}}\n{{Heritage rail insert}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Witton-le-Wear}} |route=[[Weardale Railway]] |col={{heritage rail colour|000000}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|South Church}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next=[[Etherley railway station|Etherley & Witton Park]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |route=[[Stockton and Darlington Railway]]<br /><small>Bishop Auckland & Weardale Railway</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{disused rail insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|West Auckland}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[South Durham and Lancashire Union Railway]]</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|Coundon}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Clarence Railway]]<br />(Byers Green Branch)</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{rail line |next={{rws|Hunwick}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Durham to Bishop Auckland Line]]</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{County Durham railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in County Durham]]\n[[Category:Former North Eastern Railway (UK) stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1843]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Bishop Auckland|Railway station]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Railway station in County Durham, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = Bishop Auckland\n| code         = BIA\n| image_name   = Bishop Auckland Railway Station.jpg\n| manager      = [[Northern Trains]]\n| locale       = [[Bishop Auckland]]\n| borough      = [[County Durham]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|54.6573|-1.6778|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| platforms    = 2\n<!-- | lowusage0405 = 66,681\n| lowusage0506 = {{increase}} 74,092\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 85,063\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 94,785\n| lowusage0809 = {{increase}} 96,712\n| lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 95,428\n| lowusage1011 = {{decrease}} 94,732\n| usage1112 = {{increase}} 0.101\n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.102\n| usage1314 = {{increase}} 0.109 -->\n| usage1415 = {{decrease}} 0.108\n| usage1516 = {{increase}} 0.110\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.119\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.123\n| usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.155\n| caption      = \n| owner        = \n| gridref      = NZ208291\n| original     = [[Weardale Railway|Bishop Auckland and Weardale Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n| years        = 8 November 1843\n| events       = Station opened\n| dft_category = F1\n}}\n[[File:Bishop Auckland 2 railway station1805267 f99ac746.jpg|thumb|275px|right|View westward along the main platform in 1965, providing services to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}}, and {{stnlnk|Consett}} via {{stnlnk|Crook}}]]\n[[File:Bishop Auckland 1 railway station1805295 9d064167.jpg|thumb|275px|right|View along the curved platforms in 1965, which served the former [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|NER]] line to {{stnlnk|Durham}}, and [[Clarence Railway]] via {{stnlnk|Byers Green}}]]\n[[File:Wearhead station geograph-2354909-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|275px|right|The last scheduled passenger train to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}} waits to leave Bishop Auckland on 27 June 1953, headed by ex-[[NER Class C1]] No. 65078]]\n'''Bishop Auckland railway station''' serves the town of [[Bishop Auckland]] in [[County Durham]], England. The station is the western terminus of the [[Tees Valley Line]] (also referred to as the Bishop Line West of {{stnlnk|Darlington}}) {{convert|12|mi|km}} north of Darlington.\n\nWhen it is operating, a connection can be made with the [[Weardale Railway|Weardale Heritage Railway]] at the nearby '''Bishop Auckland West railway station''' for trains towards {{stnlnk|Stanhope}}.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/timetables|title=Weardale Railway - Timetables|website=The Weardale Railway Trust|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBishop Auckland gained its first rail link in 1842,<ref>{{harvnb|Body|1988|p=43}}</ref> when the [[Stockton and Darlington Railway|Stockton and Darlington Railway (S&DR)]] backed [[Weardale Railway|Bishop Auckland and Weardale Railway (BA&WR)]] gained the powers via an [[Act of Parliament]] to build a railway line from the S&DR's station at {{stnlnk|Shildon}} via Bishop Auckland and [[Witton-le-Wear]] into [[Crook, County Durham]].<ref name=ButtP35>{{harvnb|Butt|1995|p=35}}</ref>\n\nThe company initially built a temporary terminus at [[South Church railway station|South Church]], which opened on 19 April 1842. A road coach service then extended the service into Bishop Auckland, and a secondary road coach service also ran to [[Rainton Meadows]]. After completion of the Shildon tunnel, the BA&WR erected a permanent station on the current site, which opened to freight on 8 November 1843, and passengers on 30 January 1843.<ref name=ButtP35/> All operations were sub-leased as agreed to the S&DR.<ref name=ButtP35/>\n\nIn 1844, after the [[West Durham Railway]] extended from a junction with the [[Clarence Railway]] at {{stnlnk|Byers Green}} to Crook, the S&DR extended the BA&WR from Bishop Auckland along the river valley to [[Witton-le-Wear]], and then into {{rws|Crook}}. In 1845, the S&DR came to an agreement with the [[Derwent Iron Company]] to sub-lease the southern section of the former [[Stanhope and Tyne Railway]]. It extended the line from Crook to {{stnlnk|Waskerley}} and then to [[Blackhill, Consett|Blackhill]], and it was opened as the [[Weardale Extension Railway|Weardale Extension Railway (WXR)]].<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nIn July 1845 Parliament passed the Wear Valley Act, which allowed the extension of the BA&WR from a junction at Witton-le-Wear to {{stnlnk|Frosterley}}, and a small branch line across the river to [[Bishopley]]. With all works again undertaken by the S&DR, this line opened on 3 August 1847. After these works had been completed, the BA&WR amalgamated with the WXR. All service were operated by the S&DR, which officially took over the new company in January 1857.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nOn 1 April 1857, the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway (NER)]] started a service from {{stnlnk|Durham}} to Bishop Auckland at a new terminus in Tenter Street. However, the S&DR and NER quickly came to the agreement of development of a joint station in the town, and so rebuilt the existing former BA&WR station, with NER trains using it from December 1857.<ref name=\"ButtP35\"/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nIn 1862, an Act of Parliament was passed allowing the S&DR backed [[Frosterley and Stanhope Railway]] to extend the line to {{stnlnk|Stanhope}}, thus allowing trains to transport [[limestone]] from the Newlandside Estate on the south side of the town. This brought about the extension of the [[South Durham and Lancashire Union Railway]] from {{stnlnk|Barnard Castle}} into Bishop Auckland in 1862, and with the final addition of traffic from an extension of the [[Clarence Railway]] at {{stnlnk|Byers Green}}, eventually resulted in the NER rebuilding the station again in December 1867.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nThe final extension of the Weardale Railway to {{stnlnk|Wearhead}} opened on 21 October 1895, with the NER having resited the station at {{stnlnk|Stanhope}} to provide a more suitable gradient for the heavy limestone trains. Between Eastgate and Westgate at Cambo Keels, sidings were established to serve the Weardale Iron Company's Heights limestone quarry, which is still in operation today. This final extension of the Weardale Railway bought about the final and largest layout of Bishop Auckland railway station, which was now rebuilt in triangular form with four platforms in 1905.<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>  Only three of these were normally used for passenger trains, with platform 1 handing trains towards Crook & Wearhead and platforms 2 & 3 dealing with services on the Barnard Castle, Ferryhill & Durham lines.  Platform 4 (on the chord linking the Durham & Crook lines) was mostly used for parcels & newspaper traffic and for racing pigeon specials.\n\nAs elsewhere the UK, rail traffic in the area declined after [[World War II]], with the Wearhead branch the first to lose its passenger trains in 1953. The principal closures came in the 1960s mainly as a result of the [[Beeching Axe]], with services to: Barnard Castle via [[West Auckland]] ending in June 1962; Durham in May 1964;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/bishop_auckland/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations: Bishop Auckland Station|website=www.disused-stations.org.uk}}</ref> and Crook in March 1965. This left only the former original S&DR line to {{stnlnk|Darlington}} line in operation, along with the freight-only branch traffic to [[Eastgate, County Durham|Eastgate]].<ref name=ButtP35/><ref name=DisBisAuk/>\n\nThe station remained more or less intact (although increasingly forlorn and run-down) for more than 20 years thereafter, though by the early 1980s only the former platform 3 was in use<ref name=DisBisAuk/> (along with the former Bishop Auckland East signal box).  It was eventually replaced by the current structure on 6 June 1986. This stands on the site of the former Crook branch platform, on a siding off the now single 'main' line which continues on towards Stanhope & Eastgate. The signal box was abolished at the same time, with neighbouring Shildon box assuming control of the much-simplified layout.\n\nThe remaining station buildings were then demolished and the site sold off for retail redevelopment. The former goods yard is now a supermarket with carpark, and the Durham platform is now the site of a cycling and motoring store and a bank.<ref name=DisBisAuk>{{cite web |url= http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/bishop_auckland/index10.shtml |title=Bishop Auckland |publisher=Disused Stations |date=2 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe station is currently operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]], which provides [[National Rail]] passenger services. In 2012, Bishop Trains adopted the station from [[Northern Rail (Serco-Abellio)|Northern Rail]] (the operator at the time), providing a National Rail Ticket Office and staff for the station. Bishop Trains have further developed the Ticket Office and now provide a booking service for coach trips and holidays, and more recently, rail charters.  It is staffed six days per week throughout the year (Monday to Saturday 06:50-16:15).  At all other times, tickets must be purchased in advance or on the train.  Service running information is offered by timetable posters and Bishop Trains staff (when open).  Step-free access is available from the main entrance to the ticket office and platform.<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/BIA/details.html Bishop Auckland station facilities] ''National Rail Enquiries''; Retrieved 16 February 2017</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the station was revamped. In the former toilet block, a glass front waiting room was constructed, alongside a new toilet and office.  Digital CIS displays have also been installed, as part of a scheme to provide these at all stations in the area (bar those at {{rws|Teesside Airport}} and {{rws|British Steel Redcar}}, which both have only a limited timetable).<ref>[http://www.necoastliners.co.uk/report-of-meeting-with-steve-payne-tees-valley-unlimited/ \"Report of meeting with Steve Payne, Tees Valley Unlimited\"] ''North East Coastliners'' news article 29 June 2015; Retrieved 17 February 2017</ref>\n\n===Station masters===\n{{Div col}}\n*William Crawford 1843 - 1886<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Death of and old Auckland resident |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000159/18861210/013/0003 |newspaper=Daily Gazette for Middlesbrough |location=England |date=10 December 1886 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> \n*William Boyne ???? - 1895\n*Matthew William Seymour 1895 - 1907<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.E.R. Appointments |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000726/19071214/112/0006  |newspaper=Newcastle Evening Chronicle |location=England |date=14 December 1907 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Darlington)\n*Robert Cocks 1908 - 1920<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Blyth man retiring |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002842/19201028/072/0003  |newspaper=Blyth News |location=England |date=28 October 1920 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref>  (formerly station master at Monkwearouth)\n*J.C. Pigg  1920 - 1921 (afterwards station master at Durham)\n*J.R. Winter 1922<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N.E.R. Appointments |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001634/19220503/038/0002  |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Chronicle |location=England |date=3 May 1922 |access-date=28 February 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive }}</ref> - ????\n*A. Howe 1934 - ????\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Services==\n{{Northern (train operating company) route 3}}\nTrains depart southbound to Darlington, {{stnlnk|Middlesbrough}} and {{stnlnk|Saltburn}} every hour through the day Monday to Saturday (with an additional p.m peak service).  This is an improvement from the two-hourly off-peak frequency formerly in place prior to the December 2017 timetable change.\nThe Sunday service is also now hourly until 20:00 since the timetable change in May 2018.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2018|44}}</ref>\n\n==Bishop Auckland West==\nThe [[Weardale Railway]] has built a separate platform, called '''Bishop Auckland West''', about {{convert|110|yd|m}} west of the National Rail station, from which regular passenger services to {{stnlnk|Stanhope}} initially operated from May 2010 until the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/news_2010.htm|title=Weardale Railway News 2010|access-date=4 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723070047/http://www.weardale-railway.org.uk/news_2010.htm|archive-date=23 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, the Weardale Railway Trust has operated passenger trains on selected weekdays and weekends for mostly tourist traffic using a [[British Rail Class 122|class 122 \"Bubble Car\"]]. Initially, this only ran between {{rws|Wolsingham}} and {{rws|Stanhope}} but, on 27 March 2016, this service was extended to {{rws|Witton-le-Wear}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/14386710.Trains_stop_in_County_Durham_village_for_first_time_in_50_years/|title=Trains stop in County Durham village for first time in 50 years {{!}} The Northern Echo|last=Russell|first=Helen|date=27 March 2016|website=The Northern Echo|access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref> and, after works were carried out by the Weardale Railway Trust to lift a short section of track at Broken Banks (approximately 1/2 mile west of Bishop Auckland station) to enable the embankment to be repaired (subsidence had made the line unusable for passenger traffic for a number of years prior to the works being carried out),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/16145275.Weardale_Railway_to_extend_service_to_Bishop_Auckland/|title=Weardale Railway to extend service to Bishop Auckland {{!}} The Northern Echo|last=Conner-Hill|first=Rachel|date=9 April 2018|website=The Northern Echo|access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> since July 2018, two of the three daily return services between Stanhope and Witton-le-Wear have been extended to Bishop Auckland West station.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Body |first=G. |year=1988 |title=PSL Field Guides - Railways of the Eastern Region Volume 2 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Wellingborough |isbn=1-85260-072-1 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page= |pages= |chapter= |quote= |ref=harv }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/railwaysgreatbr00whisgoog|title=The Railways of Great Britain and Ireland Practically Described and Illustrated|first=Francis|last=Whishaw|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=John Weale|year=1842|pages=32-34|oclc=833076248|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.railbrit.co.uk/location.php?loc=Bishop%20Auckland Railscot - Bishop Auckland]\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Shildon|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Tees Valley Line]]}}\n{{Heritage rail insert}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Witton-le-Wear}} |route=[[Weardale Railway]] |col={{heritage rail colour|000000}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|South Church}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next=[[Etherley railway station|Etherley & Witton Park]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |route=[[Stockton and Darlington Railway]]<br /><small>Bishop Auckland & Weardale Railway</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{disused rail insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|West Auckland}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[South Durham and Lancashire Union Railway]]</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|Coundon}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Clarence Railway]]<br />(Byers Green Branch)</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{rail line |next={{rws|Hunwick}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>|route=[[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Durham to Bishop Auckland Line]]</small> |col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{County Durham railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in County 