{"title_page": "Hessian group", "text_new": "In mathematics, the '''Hessian group''' is a [[finite group]] of order 216, introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Jordan|authorlink=Camille Jordan|year=1877}} who named it for [[Otto Hesse]]. It may be represented as the group of [[affine transformation]]s with determinant 1 of the affine plane over the field of 3 elements.<ref>Hessian group on [http://groupnames.org/index.html#?Hessian GroupNames]</ref> It has a normal subgroup that is an [[elementary abelian group]] of order 3<sup>2</sup>, and the quotient by this subgroup is isomorphic to the group SL<sub>2</sub>(3) of order 24. It also acts on the [[Hesse pencil]] of elliptic curves, and forms the [[automorphism group]] of the [[Hesse configuration]] of the 9 inflection points of these curves and the  12 lines through triples of these points.\n\nThe triple cover of this group is a [[complex reflection group]], <sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub> or {{CDD|3node|3|3node|3|3node}} of order 648, and the product of this with a group of order 2 is another complex reflection group, <sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub>[4]<sub>2</sub> or {{CDD|3node|3|3node|4|node}} of order 1296.\n\n==References==\n*{{Citation | last1=Artebani | first1=Michela | last2=Dolgachev | first2=Igor | title=The Hesse pencil of plane cubic curves | arxiv=math/0611590 |mr=2583779 | year=2009 | journal=L'Enseignement Math\u00e9matique |series=2e S\u00e9rie | issn=0013-8584 | volume=55 | issue=3 | pages=235\u2013273 | doi=10.4171/lem/55-3-3}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Coxeter | first1=Harold Scott MacDonald | author1-link=Harold Scott MacDonald Coxeter | title=The collineation groups of the finite affine and projective planes with four lines through each point |mr=0081289 | year=1956 | journal=Abhandlungen aus dem Mathematischen Seminar der Universit\u00e4t Hamburg | issn=0025-5858 | volume=20 | pages=165\u2013177 | doi=10.1007/BF03374555}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Grove | first1=Charles Clayton | title=The syzygetic pencil of cubics with a new geometrical development of its Hesse Group | url=https://archive.org/details/syzygeticpencilo00grovrich | publisher=Baltimore, Md. | year=1906}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Jordan | first1=Camille | title=M\u00e9moire sur les \u00e9quations diff\u00e9rentielles lin\u00e9aires \u00e0 int\u00e9grale alg\u00e9brique. | url=http://resolver.sub.uni-goettingen.de/purl?GDZPPN00215675X | language=French | year=1877 | journal=[[Journal f\u00fcr die reine und angewandte Mathematik]] | issn=0075-4102 | volume=84 | pages=89\u2013215 | doi=10.1515/crll.1878.84.89}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Finite groups]]\n", "text_old": "In mathematics, the '''Hessian group''' is a [[finite group]] of order 216, introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Jordan|authorlink=Camille Jordan|year=1877}} who named it for [[Otto Hesse]]. It may be represented as the group of [[affine transformation]]s with determinant 1 of the affine plane over the field of 3 elements.<ref>Hessian group on [http://groupnames.org/index.html#?Hessian GroupNames]</ref> It has a normal subgroup that is an [[elementary abelian group]] of order 3<sup>2</sup>, and the quotient by this subgroup is isomorphic to the group SL<sub>2</sub>(3) of order 24. It also acts on the [[Hesse pencil]] of elliptic curves, and forms the [[automorphism group]] of the [[Hesse configuration]] of the 9 inflection points of these curves and the  12 lines through triples of these points.\n\nThe triple cover of this group is a [[complex reflection group]], <sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub> or {{CDD|3node|3|3node|3|3node}} of order 648, and the product of this with a group of order 2 is another complex reflection group, <sub>3</sub>[3]<sub>3</sub>[4]<sub>2</sub> or {{CDD|3node|3|3node|4|node}} of order 1296.\n\n==References==\n*{{Citation | last1=Artebani | first1=Michela | last2=Dolgachev | first2=Igor | title=The Hesse pencil of plane cubic curves | arxiv=math/0611590 |mr=2583779 | year=2009 | journal=L'Enseignement Math\u00e9matique |series=2e S\u00e9rie | issn=0013-8584 | volume=55 | issue=3 | pages=235\u2013273 | doi=10.4171/lem/55-3-3}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Coxeter | first1=Harold Scott MacDonald | author1-link=Harold Scott MacDonald Coxeter | title=The collineation groups of the finite affine and projective planes with four lines through each point |mr=0081289 | year=1956 | journal=Abhandlungen aus dem Mathematischen Seminar der Universit\u00e4t Hamburg | issn=0025-5858 | volume=20 | pages=165\u2013177}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Grove | first1=Charles Clayton | title=The syzygetic pencil of cubics with a new geometrical development of its Hesse Group | url=https://archive.org/details/syzygeticpencilo00grovrich | publisher=Baltimore, Md. | year=1906}}\n*{{Citation | last1=Jordan | first1=Camille | title=M\u00e9moire sur les \u00e9quations diff\u00e9rentielles lin\u00e9aires \u00e0 int\u00e9grale alg\u00e9brique. | url=http://resolver.sub.uni-goettingen.de/purl?GDZPPN00215675X | language=French | year=1877 | journal=[[Journal f\u00fcr die reine und angewandte Mathematik]] | issn=0075-4102 | volume=84 | pages=89\u2013215 | doi=10.1515/crll.1878.84.89}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Finite groups]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Journal cites:, added 1 DOI", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hessian_group"}
