{"title_page": "Erich Topp", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Erich Topp\n|birth_date={{birth date|1914|7|2|df=y}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|2005|12|26|1914|7|2|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Hannover]]\n|death_place=[[S\u00fc\u00dfen]]\n|image=Erich Topp.jpg\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Nazi Germany}} <br />{{flag|West Germany}}\n|branch={{navy|Nazi Germany}}<br />{{navy|GER}}\n|serviceyears=1934\u201345<br/>1958\u201369\n|rank=''[[Kriegsmarine]]'': [[File:Kriegsmarine_epaulette_Fregattenkapit\u00e4n.svg|40px]] ''[[Fregattenkapit\u00e4n]]''<br />''[[Bundesmarine]]'': [[File:MDS_62_Konteradmiral_Trp.svg|20px]] ''[[Konteradmiral]]''\n|servicenumber=[[NSDAP]] #2,621,078\n|commands={{GS|U-57|1938|2}}<br/>{{GS|U-552||2}}<br />{{GS|U-3010||2}}<br/>{{GS|U-2513||2}}\n|unit=[[1st U-boat Flotilla]]<br />[[7th U-boat Flotilla]]<br />[[4th U-boat Flotilla]]<br />[[11th U-boat Flotilla]]\n|battles={{hidden\n|''See battles''\n|[[World War II]]\n* [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* [[Second Happy Time]]\n|-\n|headerstyle=background:#dbdbdb\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n|awards=[[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]]<br />[[Bundesverdienstkreuz|Great Cross of Merit]]\n|laterwork=}}\n\n'''Erich Topp''' (2 July 1914 \u2013 26 December 2005) was the third most successful of German [[U-boat|U-Boat]] commanders of [[World War II]]. He was a recipient of the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]] of [[Nazi Germany]]. He sank 35 ships for a total of {{GRT|197,460|disp=long}}. After the war he served with the Federal [[German Navy]], reaching the rank of ''[[Konteradmiral]]'' (rear admiral). He later served in [[NATO]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nTopp was born in [[Hannover]] on 2 July 1914.{{sfn|Mitcham|2012|p=258}} Topp joined the ''[[Reichsmarine]]'' on 8 April 1935 as a member of \"Crew 34\" (the incoming class of 1934).<ref group=\"Note\">The German ''[[Reichsmarine]]'' was renamed to ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' on 1 June 1935.</ref> He received his military basic training in the 2nd company in the 2nd department of the standing ship division of the [[Baltic Sea]] in [[Stralsund]] (8 April 1934&nbsp;\u2013 13 June 1934).<ref group=Tr>2nd company\u20142. ''Kompanie''</ref><ref group=Tr>2nd department\u2014II. ''Abteilung''</ref><ref group=Tr>standing ship division\u2014''Schiffsstammdivision''</ref> He was then transferred to the [[school ship]] [[Gorch Fock (1933)|''Gorch Fock'']] on 14 June 1934, and to the light cruiser {{Ship|German cruiser|Karlsruhe||2}} on 27 September 1934.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=141}} Under the command of ''Kapit\u00e4n zur See'' [[G\u00fcnther L\u00fctjens]], Topp sailed on ''Karlsruhe''{{'}}s fourth training cruise. ''Karlsruhe'' left [[Kiel]] on 22 October 1934. The ship sailed via [[Skagen]], the [[Azores]] and [[Trinidad]] on the east coast of [[South America]], passed the [[Cape Horn]], up the west coast of South, [[Middle America (Americas)|Middle]] and [[North America]] to Vancouver. At [[Callao]] (25 January \u2013 6 February 1935) they joined in the 400-year celebration of Peru. ''Karlsruhe'' returned to Kiel on 15 June 1935, travelling through the [[Panama Canal]] to [[Houston]], [[Charlestown, Saint Kitts and Nevis|Charlestown]] and [[Vigo, Spain]].{{sfn|Hildebrand|R\u00f6hr|Steinmetz|1993|p=89}}\n\nFollowing his journey on ''Karlsruhe'', Topp attended the main cadet course at the [[Naval Academy M\u00fcrwik]] (30 June 1935&nbsp;\u2013 29 June 1936).<ref group=Tr>main cadet course\u2014''Hauptlehrgang f\u00fcr F\u00e4hnriche''</ref> During this time frame at the naval academy, he advanced in rank to ''[[F\u00e4hnrich zur See]]'' (officer cadet) on 1 July 1935. Starting on 30 June 1936, he underwent a number of specialized weapons training courses for cadets at various naval schools.<ref group=Tr>weapons course for cadets\u2014''Waffenlehrgang f\u00fcr F\u00e4hnriche''</ref> On 16 October 1936, he was again transferred to ''Karlsruhe'', staying onboard until 31 March 1937. The next day, he was promoted to ''[[Leutnant zur See]]'' (Second Lieutenant) and took a torpedo training course which he completed on 17 April. On 18 April, he was yet again posted to ''Karlsruhe'', serving as an [[adjutant]] until 4 October 1937.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=141}}\n\nOn 5 October 1937, Topp started his U-boat training at the U-boat school in [[Neustadt in Holstein]] before he became an instruction officer at the naval non-commissioned officer training department in Friedrichsort, a borough of Kiel, on 2 June 1938.<ref group=Tr>naval non-commissioned officer training department\u2014M.L.A ''Marineunteroffizierslehrabteilung''</ref>  Topp was then posted to the [[7th U-boat Flotilla|Wegener Flotilla]] on 26 September 1938. There, he was appointed 1st watch officer on {{GS|U-46|1938|2}} under the command of ''[[Kapit\u00e4nleutnant]]'' [[Herbert Sohler]]. On 1 April 1939, Topp was promoted to ''[[Oberleutnant zur See]]'' (sub-lieutenant).{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=142}}\n\n===National Socialism===\nIn May 1933, Topp joined the [[Nazi Party]] and in 1934 also joined the ''[[Allgemeine-SS]]''.{{sfn|Mulligan|2013|p=}} Topp took the [[Hitler oath]], convinced it was the \"right thing to do.\"{{sfn|Rust|1993|p=157}} To the beginning of the war at least, his peers regarded Topp as a Nazi.{{sfn|Vause|1997|p=96}} Topp made the acquaintance of [[Martin Bormann]], Hitler's personal secretary and head of the [[Nazi Party Chancellery]]. Bormann married the sister of Topp's crew mate, Walter Buch. Topp was close enough to be invited to Bormann's residence in [[Berchtesgaden]].{{sfn|Topp|1992|p=98}} Topp's political outlook was not shared by his uncle. His aunt through marriage, Anna Topp, was [[Jewish]]. During the Nazi reign she was sent to and survived the [[Theresienstadt Ghetto]]. {{sfn|Topp|1992|pp=120, 129\u2013131}} In his memoirs Topp claimed not to have believed in [[Nazi ideology]].{{sfn|Topp|1992|p=125}} One analyst wrote, \"the contrasts and Topp's individual course make obvious the limitations of any quantitative study\" [of his political convictions].{{sfn|Mulligan|2013|p=}}\n\nTopp came to terms with the Nazi regime and its crimes postwar.{{sfn|Mulligan|2013|p=}} He entered into heated arguments with former comrades over the cause for which they fought. Topp was particularly critical of Admiral [[Karl D\u00f6nitz]], commander-in-chief of U-boats and later the ''Kriegsmarine''.{{sfn|Mulligan|2013|p=}} After the war, Topp expressed his view that the German naval command, and his superior Karl D\u00f6nitz, knew of the [[Holocaust]].{{sfn|Rust|1993|p=158}} Topp referenced D\u00f6nitz's commitment to [[National Socialism]], admiration for Hitler, and his presence at the [[Posen speeches]]. Topp was critical of D\u00f6nitz's pretensions to have been an apolitical soldier.{{sfn|Rust|1993|pp=158\u2013159}} Topp said of D\u00f6nitz, that his failure to do anything about it \"comes very close to a passive toleration of these insane crimes.\"{{sfn|Vause|1997|p=195}} Few former U-boat commanders were as vocal in attacking D\u00f6nitz's character. His aunt's experiences in the ghetto from 1943 may have been a factor.{{sfn|Vause|1997|p=195}} D\u00f6nitz confronted Topp personally when the later called upon him. He purportedly greeted Topp with a question, \"I understand you think I should have been executed!?\"{{sfn|Rust|1993|p=159}} He presented Topp with his accusation, underlined, and a letter from [[Samuel Eliot Morison]], the official historian of the [[United States Navy]], which accepted D\u00f6nitz's defence that he knew nothing of the Nazi crimes. It was Morrison that told D\u00f6nitz of Topp's accusations, or \"doubts\", as Topp later claimed they were.{{sfn|Rust|1993|p=159}}\n\n==World War II==\n[[World War II]] commenced following the [[Invasion of Poland (1939)|German invasion of Poland]] on 1 September 1939. ''U-46'', under the command of Sohler, had already been at sea since 19 August, returning to port on 15 September. Topp sailed on three further patrols on ''U-46'' (3 October \u2013 7 November 1939, 19 December 1939 \u2013 10 January 1940 and 11 March \u2013 23 April 1940). During these patrols, ''U-46'' sank one ship of {{GRT|7,028|disp=long}} on 17 October and another ship of {{GRT|924|link=off}} on 21 December.{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|pp=19, 28}} For his service on ''U-46'', Topp was awarded the [[U-boat War Badge]] ({{lang|de|U-Boot-Kriegsabzeichen}}) on 7 November 1939 and the [[Iron Cross]] 2nd Class ({{lang|de|Eisernes Kreuz zweiter Klasse}}) in January 1940. On 1 May 1940, he was transferred to the [[1st U-boat Flotilla]].{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=142}}\n\n===Command of ''U-57''===\nAfter eight war patrols under the command of ''Kapit\u00e4nleutnant'' [[Claus Korth]], command of {{GS|U-57|1938|2}} of the [[1st U-boat Flotilla]] was passed to Topp on 5 June 1940. Topp's fifth war patrol began in Kiel on 11 July 1940 and was destined for the [[North Atlantic]], into the [[North Channel (Great Britain and Ireland)|North Channel]], and [[The Minch]]. Because the ''[[Gruppenhorchger\u00e4t]]'', a [[hydrophone]] [[Phased array|array]], was experiencing technical difficulties, Topp took ''U-57''  to port for repairs. ''U-57'' arrived in Bergen on 15 July, departed again that day only to return to Bergen on 20 July. Two days later, ''U-57'' was able to begin its patrol. The ''[[Befehlshaber der U-Boote]]'' (BdU\u2014supreme commander of the U-boat arm) credited Topp with the sinking three ships of {{GRT|12,773|link=off}} of shipping. On 7 August, ''U-57'' arrived in [[Lorient]], France.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=143}}{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|pp=61, 63}}\n\nOn 14 August 1940, ''U-57'' departed from Lorient on its tenth war patrol. Again Topp led ''U-57'' into the North Atlantic, the North Channel and the [[Hebrides]]. On this patrol, Kretschmer sank three ships of {{GRT|24,088|link=off}}, and damaged another ship of {{GRT|5,407|link=off}}. On 3 September 1940, ''U-57'' collided with the Norwegian vessel ''Rona'' near the [[Lock (water navigation)|lock]] at [[Brunsb\u00fcttel]] and sank.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142\u2013143}} Following the loss of ''U-57'' \u2014 the boat was later raised and used for training purposes \u2014 Topp was awarded Iron Cross 1st Class ({{lang|de|Eisernes Kreuz erster Klasse}}) and initially remained with 1st U-boat Flotilla. On 4 November, he was sent to [[Blohm & Voss]], the shipbuilding works in [[Hamburg]], for construction training of {{GS|U-552||2}}, a [[Type VII U-boat|Type VIIC U-boat]].{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=143}}\n\n===Transfer to ''U-552''===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101II-MW-3676-28, St. Nazaire, Uboot U 552.jpg|thumb|left|''U-552'' returning to St. Nazaire, Koitschka standing left of Topp]]\nOn 4 December 1940, Topp took command of ''U-552'' and commissioned the U-boat into the [[7th U-boat Flotilla]]. Following sea trials and training, Topp, with ''Leutnant zur See'' [[Siegfried Koitschka]] as his second watch officer, took ''U-552'' on its first war patrol on 13 February 1941. The patrol which was destined for the North Atlantic west of Ireland began in Kiel. That day, they headed for Brunsb\u00fcttel where they stayed one day. The following day, ''U-552'' made a stopover at [[Cuxhaven]] before leaving for [[Heligoland]] on 15 February. After three days at Heligoland, Topp took the boat into the North Atlantic. ''U-552''{{'}}s first patrol ended in [[Saint-Nazaire]], France on 16 March 1941.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=143}} On this patrol, Topp sank two ships of {{GRT|12,749|link=off}}.{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=105}}\n\nThe second patrol on ''U-552'' began on 7 April 1941 from Saint-Nazaire and targeted the shipping routes in the North Atlantic, south of [[Iceland]]. On this patrol, the BdU credited Topp with the sinking of three ships and one escort totaling {{GRT|24,319|link=off}}. The patrol ended on 6 May, again in Saint-Nazaire.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=144}} In reality, Topp sank three ships totaling {{GRT|15,970|link=off}}, and damaged one ship of {{GRT|8,190|link=off}} which was then sunk by {{GS|U-201||2}} ([[Adalbert Schnee]]).{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=117}} On 25 May, Topp took ''U-552'' on its third war patrol. The next day, ''U-552'' returned to Saint-Nazaire before heading for North Channel on 3 June. The BdU assumed that Topp sank three ships of {{GRT|25,548|link=off}} and he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] ({{lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes}}) on 20 June 1941. This patrol ended on 2 July in Saint-Nazaire.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142, 144}} Later analysis revealed that the true tonnage sunk accumulated to {{GRT|24,401|link=off}}.{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=130}} One of the ships was the {{GRT|10,948|link=off}} [[List of shipwrecks in June 1941#18 June|''Norfolk'']]. The vessel carried mail an steel plates among 4,000 tons of general cargo. Captain Frederick Lougheed and 69 men were saved; one man was lost.{{sfn|Tennent|2001|p=134}}\n\n''[[Korvettenkapit\u00e4n]]'' [[Harro Schacht]] was Topp's cammander in training on ''U-552''{{'}}s fourth war patrol. The patrol, which began on 18 August and ended on 26 August in Saint-Nazaire, resulted in the sinking of one ship of {{GRT|2,129|link=off}}.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=144}} This ship had previously been damaged by {{GS|U-564||2}} ([[Reinhard Suhren]]).{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=154}} Following this patrol, Topp was promoted to ''[[Kapit\u00e4nleutnant]]'' (Captain Lieutenant) on 1 September 1941. The fifth war patrol took ''U-552'' into the North Atlantik, patrolling southeast of [[Greenland]]. Topp left Saint-Nazaire on 4 September and sank three ships of {{GRT|18,687|link=off}}. ''U-552'' returned to Saint-Nazaire on 5 October.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142, 144}}{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=167}}\n\n===''Reuben James'' and Second Happy time===\nThe next patrol began on 25 October and ended on 26 November 1941 in Saint-Nazaire. This was also Koitschka's last war patrol as first watch officer on ''U-552''.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=144}}{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=181}} On ''U-552''{{'}}s sixth war patrol into the North Atlantic, east of [[Grand Banks of Newfoundland]], Topp sank the [[destroyer]] {{USS|Reuben James|DD-245|6}} on 31 October 1941, the first [[United States Navy]] warship to be lost in World War II while it escorted [[Convoy HX 156]].{{sfn|Milner|2011|p=73}} The torpedo struck a forward magazine, blowing the ship apart. All of her officers and over 100 of the crew went down with the ship.{{sfn|Padfield|1995|p=164}} The destruction of the ''Reuben James'' facilitated a worsening of already rapidly deteriorating diplomatic relations between [[Nazi Germany]] and the still nominally neutral [[United States of America]]. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] used the incident to shift public opinion toward a confrontational stance with the European [[Axis powers]].{{sfn|Padfield|1995|pp=164\u2013165}} Support for the [[Neutrality Acts of the 1930s]] gradually eroded. On 13 November 1941 amendments to the act allowed for the arming of US merchant ships, their operation in the war zone, and active assistance to the [[British Empire]] to increase the tonnage available to it.{{sfn|Padfield|1995|pp=164\u2013165}} Hitler and the [[List of Nazi Party leaders and officials|Nazi leadership]] wished to keep the US neutral and the order to minimise contact at sea remained in force, at least until [[Operation Barbarossa]] had destroyed the [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Padfield|1995|pp=164\u2013165}} Roosevelt did not publicly mention the destroyer was escorting a British convoy, was not flying the [[Ensign of the United States]], and was in the process of dropping [[depth charge]]s on another U-boat when it was engaged and sunk.{{sfn|Mitcham|2012|p=258}}\n\nOn 11 December 1941, Hitler declared war on the United States. D\u00f6nitz ordered immediate offensive operations off the [[East Coast of the United States]]. Codenamed [[Operation Drumbeat]] (''Unternehmen Paukenschlag''), the U-boat fleet inflicted the largest naval defeat on the [[United States Navy]] in history.{{sfn|Gannon|1990|pp=308, 339, 389}} Though few in number at the beginning\u2014just five\u2014the U-boats pressed home attacks close to the shore, from [[Newfoundland]] to the [[Gulf of Mexico]].{{sfn|Gannon|1990|p=77}} The American failure to initialise a [[Blackout (wartime)|blackout]], ship captains' insistence on following peace-time procedures, and lack of effective [[Anti-submarine weapon|naval defences]] contributed to high losses.{{sfn|Terraine|1989|p=410}}{{sfn|Milner|2011|p=81}} 397 ships were sunk during Drumbeat.{{sfn|Gannon|1990|p=389}} The Germans termed this period, the \"Second Happy Time.\"{{sfn|Milner|2011|p=80}} Topp crossed the Atlantic and joined [[Wolfpack Zieten]].{{sfn|Gannon|1990|p=225}}\n\n''Oberleutnant zur See'' [[Albrecht Brandi]] joined Topp's crew as a commander in training on ''U-552''{{'}}s seventh war patrol. The patrol to the West Atlantik, [[Grand Banks]] of Newfoundland, and [[Nova Scotia]] started on 25 December in Saint-Nazaire. Topp sank three ships totaling {{GRT|10,560|link=off}} before returning to Saint-Nazaire on 27 January 1942.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=144}} Topp experienced mechanical problems with his torpedoes. On 15 January he expended four on the small merchant ship [[List of shipwrecks in January 1942#15 January|''Dayrose'']] from a range of 800 metres before a fifth sank it. Topp signalled BdU about the incident.{{sfn|Gannon|1990|p=226}}{{sfn|Hadley|1985|p=65}} Topp experienced the same problems in the sinking of [[List of shipwrecks in January 1942#18 January|''Frances Salman'']], five miles south of [[Cape Race]]. Repeated failures were psychologically unnerving. Unable to load the spare torpedoes from deck stowage due to icing and inclement weather, BdU called him home.{{sfn|Hadley|1985|p=67}} \n\nThe eighth war patrol took ''U-552'' to West Atlantic and to the [[East Coast of the United States]]. Topp left Saint-Nazaire on 7 March, returning on 27 April. On this patrol, he sank seven ships with a total tonnage of {{GRT|45,731|link=off}}.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=144\u2013145}}{{sfn|Rohwer|H\u00fcmmelchen|1968|p=228}} While at sea, Topp received the message on 11 April that he had been awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves]] ({{lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub}}). He was the 87th member of the Wehrmacht to be so honoured. On 11 April, [[Karl D\u00f6nitz]] also awarded him the U-boat War Badge with Diamonds ({{lang|de|U-Boot-Kriegsabzeichen mit Brillanten}}).{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142, 145}}\n\nTopp's sinking of the {{SS|David H. Atwater}} has cast a shadow on his conduct in action. When he spotted the coastal steamer off [[Chincoteague, Virginia]] on 3 April 1942, he surfaced ''U-552'', overtook it from astern, and, without offering the Captain the chance to surrender, attacked it with his deck gun from 600 yards, firing a total of 93 rounds. Captain Bill Webster was killed in the shelling. ''Atwater's'' civilian [[United States Merchant Marine|Merchant Marine]] crew of 27 suffered 24 lost lives during the attack.{{sfn|Bridgland|2001|p=216}} According to one account, when [[United States Coast Guard Cutter]] number 218 ''Legare'' appeared, it found the ship sunk with only several feet of its mast still visible. Bodies were seen, including one in a lifeboat riddle with machine gun holes.{{sfn|Bridgland|2001|p=216}}{{sfn|Ben-Yehuda|2016|p=185}}\n\nTopp's ninth war patrol on ''U-552'' went to the North Atlantic, west of Spain. Leaving Saint-Nazaire on 9 June, Topp sank five ships totalling {{GRT|15,825|link=off}} before returning to port ten days later.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=145}} Topp formed part of a strong wolf pack against [[Convoy HG 84]]. Topp engaged the convoy {{convert|400|nmi|mi km|abbr=off}} west-northwest of [[A Coru\u00f1a]]. Topp achieved all his successes on this patrol against HG&nbsp;84.{{sfn|Tennent|2001|p=204}} On his tenth and last war patrol on ''U-552'', Topp sank two ships of {{GRT|14,555|link=off}} and damaged two further of {{GRT|18,720|link=off}}. Topp had left Saint-Nazaire on 4 July and returned from the North Atlantic on 13 August.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=145}} Upon his return, he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]] ({{lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub und Schwertern}}) on 17 August. He was the 17th member of the Wehrmacht to be so honored. That day, he also received a preferential promotion to ''[[Korvettenkapit\u00e4n]]'' (Corvette Captain) and D\u00f6nitz presented him an honorary dagger of the ''Kriegsmarine'' with Diamonds.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142, 145}}\n\n===Ashore===\n[[File:U-2513 off Key West.jpg|thumb|right|''U-2513'' off Key West, October 1946]]\nCommand of ''U-552'' was passed on to ''Kapit\u00e4nleutnant'' Klaus Popp. Topp officially remained with the 7th U-boat Flotilla until 4 November when he was appointed chief of the [[27th U-boat Flotilla]], a training flotilla based in [[Gotenhafen]] (now [[Gdynia]], [[Poland]]). In August 1944, Topp was appointed head of the department charged with introducing the [[Type XXI submarine]]s into service, the first submarines designed to operate primarily submerged. In this position, he was promoted to ''[[Fregattenkapit\u00e4n]]'' (Frigate Captain) on 1 December 1944.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=142}}\n\nOn 23 March 1945, he was appointed commander of {{GS|U-3010||2}} in the [[4th U-boat Flotilla]], and commander of {{GS|U-2513||2}} in the [[11th U-boat Flotilla]] on 26 April. On 20 May 1945, Topp was taken [[prisoner of war]] in [[Krager\u00f8]], Norway. He was released on 17 August 1945.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|pp=142\u2013143}} Topp's boat, ''U-2513'', was tested by the United States Navy. American reports concluded at twelve knots submerged speed she is quieter than our best fleet submarines at six....up to ten knots she is extremely quiet.\"{{sfn|Milner|2011|p=254}} The same report concluded at least seven ships were required to carry out a search for the XXI submarine.{{sfn|Milner|2011|p=254}}\n\n==Later life and Bundesmarine==\n[[File:M\u00fclheim adR - Bergstra\u00dfe - Theodor-Heuss-Platz+Stadthalle 03 ies.jpg|thumb|left|Prof. Gerhard Graubner and Topp designed and built the ''Stadthalle'' (city's event hall) in [[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]].]]\nOn 4 June 1946, he started at the [[Leibniz University Hannover|Technical University of Hannover]], studying architecture, and graduated in 1950 with a degree in engineering. He also served as technical advisor for the 1957 film [[Sharks and Little Fish]].{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 3 March 1958, Topp joined [[West Germany]]'s navy, at the time named the ''[[Bundesmarine]]'' (Federal Navy), holding the rank of ''Fregattenkapit\u00e4n''. His first assignment was with the [[Armed Forces Staff (Germany)|''F\u00fchrungsstab der Marine'']] (Navy Staff). On 16 August 1958, he served with the [[NATO Military Committee]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], initially as a naval speaker, later as the [[chief-of-staff]] of the German delegation in Washington. During this assignment, he was promoted to ''[[Kapit\u00e4n zur See]]'' (captain at sea/captain) on 1 November 1959. On 1 January 1962, Topp was transferred to the position of commander of the ''Bundesmarine''{{'}}s [[:de:Amphibische Gruppe|''Amphibische Streitkr\u00e4fte'']] (\"amphibious forces\"), a position he held until 30 September 1963. In parallel, on 1 November 1962, he was made acting commander of [[:de:Ubootflottille|U-boats]], serving in this capacity until 1 December 1962.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=143}}\n\nTopp was then appointed chief-of-staff of the [[:de:Flottenkommando|''Flottenkommando'']] (Fleet Command) on 1 October 1963. On 1 July 1965, he headed the sub command department with ''F\u00fchrungsstab der Marine'' in the [[Federal Ministry of Defence (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Defence]].<ref group=Tr>head of the sub command department\u2014''Leiter der Unterabteilung F\u00fchrung''</ref> There, Topp was promoted to ''[[Flottillenadmiral]]'' (flotilla admiral) on 15 November 1965. On 1 October 1966, Topp was named deputy [[Inspector of the Navy]] and at the same time became the chief of the ''F\u00fchrungsstab der Marine'' in the Federal Ministry of Defence. In this role, Topp was promoted to ''[[Konteradmiral]]'' (Counter Admiral) on 21 December 1966. Topp held this position until 30 September 1969. He then continued to serve with Inspector of the Navy until his retirement on 31 December 1969. For his service with the ''Bundesmarine'', Topp was awarded the Commander's Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] ({{lang|de|Gro\u00dfes Verdienstkreuz des Verdienstordens der Bundesrepublik Deutschland}}) on 19 September 1969.{{sfn|Busch|R\u00f6ll|2003|p=143}}\n\nIn 1968, Topp had been considered as head of the Plans & Policy department with the [[Allied Forces Northern Europe]] (AFNORTH) in [[Kols\u00e5s]], Norway which at the time was headed by the German ''Konteradmiral'' Heinrich Erdmann. The [[Supreme Allied Commander Europe]] (SACEUR), US General [[Lyman Lemnitzer]], had originally approved this nomination. In order to not unnecessarily stress the German-Norwegian relationship, Topp had sunk four Norwegian vessels in World War II, Lemnitzer later decided against Topp and appointed ''Konteradmiral'' [[Friedrich Guggenberger]] instead.{{sfn|Gablik|1996|p=129}}\n\nAfter retiring from the Bundesmarine, for a few years Topp was a technical advisor to the German shipyard [[HDW]] AG.  His service as a NATO advisor was loosely portrayed (as \"Commodore Wolfgang Schrepke\") in the 1965 movie ''[[The Bedford Incident]]''. His memoirs \"The Odyssey of a U-Boat Commander: The Recollections of Erich Topp\" was published in 1992. When Topp was asked in 1996 by publisher/historian [[Theodore P. Savas]] to contribute a Foreword for a collection of essays on German U-boat commanders, he instead submitted a contribution about his close friend [[Engelbert Endrass]], who was lost with his crew and boat {{GS|U-567||2}} off Gibraltar in late December 1941. Topp had privately penned the piece about their friendship on his next patrol to the east coast of America, but had never submitted it for publication. The essay was translated from German and footnoted by Dr. Eric Rust, and appeared as the opening chapter in \"Silent Hunters: German U-boat Commanders of World War II\" (1997, 2003, 2005). Savas also recruited Topp to serve as the technical adviser for the 2001 submarine simulation computer game [[Silent Hunter II]], and a series of interviews with him appears in the game.{{sfn|Bub|1999}} He was interviewed on World War II submarine operations for the [[Nova (American TV series)|Nova (TV series)]] special [[Hitler's Lost Sub]], which detailed the efforts of a team of divers, led by [[John Chatterton]] and [[Richie Kohler]] to identify an unknown German U-Boat wreck 65 miles off the coast of New Jersey; the wreck was identified as {{GS|U-869||2}}.{{sfn|Der Spiegel Die letzte Feindfahrt}}\n\nTopp died on 26 December 2005, in [[S\u00fc\u00dfen]] at the age of 91; he was survived by two sons, Peter Kay (1945-2015) and Michael (b. 1950), and five grandchildren.\n\n==Summary of career==\n\n===Ships attacked===\nAs commander of {{GS|U-57|1938|2}} and {{GS|U-552||2}}, Topp is credited with the sinking of 35 ships for a total of {{GRT|197,460|disp=long}}, further damaging four ships of {{GRT|32,317}} and sinking one warship, {{USS|Reuben James|DD-245|6}}, of {{convert|1190|LT|abbr=off}}, killing a total of approximately 822 crew, troops and passengers.\n{{Clear}}\n{|class=\"wiki