Vitali Klitschko]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Comeback of the Year#2000s|''The Ring'' Comeback of the Year]]\n|years=2009}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Bernard Hopkins]]}}\n{{s-before|rows=2|before=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Best Fighter ESPY Award\n|years=2010}}\n{{s-after|after=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Best Fighter ESPY Award\n|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Ronda Rousey]]}}\n{{s-before|before=[[Evander Holyfield]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Fighter of the Year#1990s|''The Ring'' Fighter of the Year]]\n|years=1998}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Paulie Ayala]]}}\n{{s-before|rows=2|before=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Fighter of the Year#2000s|''The Ring'' Fighter of the Year]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-after|rows=2|after=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Sugar Ray Robinson Award#2000s|BWAA Fighter of the Year]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-before|before=[[Nonito Donaire]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Sugar Ray Robinson Award#2010s|BWAA Fighter of the Year]]\n|years=2013}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Terence Crawford]]}}\n{{s-before|before=Terence Crawford}}\n{{s-ttl|title=BWAA Fighter of the Year\n|years=2015}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Carl Frampton]]}}\n{{s-before|before=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Sugar Ray Robinson Award#2010s|BWAA Fighter of the Decade]]\n|years=2010s}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=Bernard Hopkins}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Boxing pound for pound rankings#The Ring|''The Ring'' pound for pound #1 boxer]]\n|years=July 17, 2005 \u2013 June 7, 2008<br>Retired}}\n{{s-aft|after=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-bef|before=Manny Pacquiao}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''The Ring'' pound for pound #1 boxer\n|years=December 8, 2012 \u2013 September 12, 2015<br>Retired}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rom\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez (boxer)|Rom\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Floyd Mayweather}}\n{{ESPY Best Fighter}}\n{{Ring magazine Fighter of the Year}}\n{{Sugar Ray Robinson Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayweather Jr., Floyd}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American boxers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Boxers from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Michigan]]\n[[Category:International Boxing Federation champions]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in boxing]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Brunswick, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Council champions]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Association champions]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Organization champions]]\n[[Category:International Boxing Organization champions]]\n[[Category:The Ring champions]]\n[[Category:Light-flyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Flyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:National Golden Gloves champions]]\n[[Category:Featherweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Boxing promoters]]\n[[Category:Undefeated world boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World super-featherweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World lightweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World light-welterweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World welterweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World light-middleweight boxing champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Floyd Mayweather|his father|Floyd Mayweather Sr.}}\n<!--as Floyd Mayweather redirects here-->\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|American boxer and boxing promoter}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Floyd Mayweather Jr.\n| image = Floyd Mayweather, Jr. at DeWalt event (5888721735) (rotated 4).jpg\n| caption = Mayweather in June 2011\n| realname = Floyd Joy Mayweather Jr.\n| nickname = {{plainlist|\n*Pretty Boy\n*Money\n*TBE\n}}\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Super featherweight]]\n*[[Lightweight]]\n*[[Light welterweight]]\n*[[Welterweight]]\n*[[Light middleweight]]\n}}\n| height = 5 ft 8 in\n| reach = 72 in\n| nationality = American\n| birth_name = Floyd Joy Sinclair\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|2|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], U.S.\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 50\n| wins = 50\n| KO = 27\n| losses = 0\n|Years active 1996-2015, 2017\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Boxing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Featherweight|1996 Atlanta]] | [[Featherweight]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Floyd Joy Mayweather Jr.''' (born '''Floyd Joy Sinclair'''; February 24, 1977) is an American [[professional boxing]] [[promoter (entertainment)|promoter]] and former professional boxer. He competed from 1996 to 2007, 2009 to 2010, 2011 to 2015, and made a one-fight comeback in [[Floyd Mayweather vs. Conor McGregor|2017]]. During his career, he won fifteen major world titles including [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'']] in [[quintuple champion|five weight classes]] and the [[lineal championship]] in four weight classes (twice at [[welterweight]]), and [[list of undefeated boxing world champions|retired with an undefeated record]]. As an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], Mayweather won a bronze medal in the [[featherweight]] division at the [[1996 Olympics]], three [[U.S. Golden Gloves]] championships (at [[light flyweight]], [[flyweight]], and featherweight), and the [[United States national amateur boxing championships|U.S. national championship]] at featherweight.\n\nMayweather was named [[Sugar Ray Robinson Award#2010s|\"Fighter of the Decade\"]] for the 2010s by the [[Boxing Writers Association of America]] (BWAA), a two-time winner of [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'' magazine's]] [[Ring magazine Fighter of the Year|Fighter of the Year]] award (1998 and 2007), a three-time winner of the [[Sugar Ray Robinson Award|BWAA Fighter of the Year]] award (2007, 2013, and 2015), and a six-time winner of the [[Best Fighter ESPY Award]] (2007\u20132010, 2012\u20132014).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nowboxing.com/2010/07/floyd-mayweather-wins-espy-beats-pacquiao-and-georges-st-pierre/12044/ |title=Floyd Mayweather wins ESPY Award beating out Manny Pacquiao & Georges St-Pierre |publisher=www.nowboxing.com |accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/179759-mayweather-wins-fifth-espy-award|title=Mayweather wins fifth ESPY award|website=Ringtv.craveonline.com|accessdate=December 27, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184759/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/179759-mayweather-wins-fifth-espy-award|archivedate=October 29, 2013}}</ref> In 2016, Mayweather was ranked by [[ESPN]] as the greatest boxer, [[pound for pound]], of the last 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/14970037/ranking-top-25-pound-pound-boxers-25-years |title=#P4Prank: Ranking top 25 pound-for-pound boxers of past 25 years |website=Espn.go.com |date=April 8, 2016 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> He remains [[BoxRec]]'s number one fighter of all time, pound for pound, as well as the greatest welterweight of his era.<ref name=\"boxrec.com\">{{cite web |url=http://boxrec.com/records |title=BoxRec Ratings |website=Boxrec.com |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104115343/http://boxrec.com/records |archivedate=January 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingnewsandviews.com/2016/06/13/boxrec-rank-mayweather/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815054330/https://www.boxingnewsandviews.com/2016/06/13/boxrec-rank-mayweather/ |archivedate=August 15, 2016  }}</ref> Many sporting news and boxing websites, including ''The Ring'', ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', ESPN, BoxRec, [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]], and [[Yahoo! Sports]], ranked Mayweather as the best pound for pound boxer in the world twice in a span of ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/ratings |title=Ring Ratings, Pound for Pound |publisher=ringtv.craveonline.com |accessdate=October 24, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503014133/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/ratings |archivedate=May 3, 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/mma/boxing/pound-for-pound-ratings/index.html |title=Pound-For-Pound Top 15 |work=Sports Illustrated |date=November 14, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/boxing/lists/Boxing-pound-for-pound-list-061511#photo-title=Floyd%20Mayweather%20Jr.,%20welterweight%20%20(42-0,%2026%20KOs)&photo=29899156 |title=Boxing pound-for-pound top 10 |publisher=Foxsports |date=November 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/7241680/ranking-top-pound-pound-boxers-nos-1-3 |title=Top three pound-for-pound fighters |publisher=ESPN |date=November 16, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://boxrec.com |title=Boxing Records, Lb for Lb |publisher=boxrec.com |accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/box/news;_ylt=AgN1F2OevG7ctQ0BN94sjIqUxLYF?slug=ki-iole_rankings_mayweather_pacquiao111711 |title=Rankings: Mayweather takes over top spot |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=November 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603101815/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/boxer-mayweather-due-begin-vegas-182523834--box.html |archivedate=June 3, 2012  }}</ref> In 2020, Mayweather was ranked second on [[Ranker]]'s list of best boxers of the [[21st century]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranker.com/list/best-boxers-of-the-21st-century/ranker-sports|title=The Best Boxers of the 21st Century|publisher=[[Ranker]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportbible.com/boxing/news-top-10s-the-50-greatest-boxers-of-the-21st-century-have-been-named-20200212|title=The 50 Greatest Boxers Of The 21st Century Have Been Named|publisher=SportBible}}</ref>\n\nHe is often referred to as the best defensive boxer in history, as well as being the most accurate puncher since the existence of [[CompuBox]], having the highest plus\u2013minus ratio in recorded boxing history.<ref>Guryashkin, Igor, [http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/7780088/floyd-mayweather-jr-measures-boxing-greats \"Mayweather measures up with greats\"], ESPN, May 3, 2012.</ref><ref>Manfred, Tony, [http://www.businessinsider.com/boxers-explain-why-floyd-mayweather-is-so-good-2015-4 \"The fighters who've lost to Floyd Mayweather explain why he's so impossible to beat\"], ''Business Insider'', April 30, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/floyd-mayweather-s-flawed-perfect-record-and-how-he-would-have-fared-against-all-time-greats-200808078.html|author=Iole, Kevin |date=September 10, 2015|title=Floyd Mayweather's flawed perfect record and how he would have fared against all-time greats|work=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> Mayweather has a record of 26 consecutive wins in world title fights (10 by [[knockout|KO]]), 23 wins (9 KOs) in lineal title fights, 24 wins (7 KOs) against former or current world titlists, 12 wins (3 KOs) against former or current lineal champions, and 3 wins (1 KO) against [[International Boxing Hall of Fame]] inductees.\n\nMayweather is one of the most lucrative [[pay-per-view]] attractions of all time, in any sport. He topped the ''[[Forbes]]'' and ''Sports Illustrated'' lists of the 50 highest-paid athletes of 2012 and 2013, and the ''Forbes'' list again in both 2014 and 2015,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11463404 | work=The New Zealand Herald | title=Sport's richest athletes named | date=June 11, 2014 |access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/athletes/list/ |title=2015 Ranking The World's Highest Paid Athletes List}}</ref> listing him as the highest paid athlete in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/18504482 |title=Floyd Mayweather knocks Tiger Woods off the top of Forbes list |date=June 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/18/sports/behind-the-scenes-haymon-is-shaking-up-the-fight-game.html |work=The New York Times |first=Greg |last=Bishop |title=Al Haymon Quietly Shakes Up Boxing | date=December 17, 2011}}</ref> In 2006, he founded his own boxing promotional firm, [[Mayweather Promotions]], after leaving [[Bob Arum]]'s [[Top Rank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2420382 |title=Mayweather turns down $8M to fight Margarito |publisher=Espn.com |date=April 25, 2006}}</ref> Mayweather has generated approximately 24&nbsp;million PPV buys and $1.67&nbsp;billion in revenue throughout his career, surpassing the likes of former top PPV attractions including [[Mike Tyson]], [[Evander Holyfield]], [[Lennox Lewis]], [[Oscar De La Hoya]] and [[Manny Pacquiao]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php?title=Human:352#Pay-Per-View_History |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. |website=BoxRec.com |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2015}}\nFloyd Joy Mayweather Jr. was born Floyd Joy Sinclair on February 24, 1977, in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], into a family of [[Boxing|boxers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/athlete/floyd-mayweather|title=Floyd Mayweather|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> His father, [[Floyd Mayweather Sr.]], was a former welterweight contender who fought Hall of Famer [[Sugar Ray Leonard]]. His uncles [[Jeff Mayweather|Jeff]] and [[Roger Mayweather]] were professional boxers, with the latter\u2014Floyd's former trainer\u2014winning two world championships, as well as fighting Hall of Famers [[Julio C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez]], [[Pernell Whitaker]], and [[Kostya Tszyu]]. Mayweather was born with his mother's last name,<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Chuck |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/boxing/2007-12-05-mayweather-cover_N.htm |title=Mayweather dancing with success in and out of ring |date=December 6, 2007 |accessdate=April 15, 2014 |publisher=USA Today}}</ref> but his last name would change to Mayweather shortly thereafter. His maternal grandfather was born in Kingston, [[Jamaica]].<ref>{{YouTube|gEAIWUxecvk|Floyd Mayweather is a Jamaican Yardie (big tings)}}</ref> He attended [[Ottawa Hills High School (Michigan)|Ottawa Hills High School]] before dropping out.\n\nBoxing has been a part of Mayweather's life since his childhood and he never seriously considered any other profession. \"I think my grandmother saw my potential first,\" he said. \"When I was young, I told her, 'I think I should get a job.' She said, 'No, just keep boxing.'\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown |first=Clifton |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/08/sports/othersports/08boxing.html |title=Mayweather Tries to Win Fourth Title  |work=The New York Times |date=April 8, 2006 |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> During the 1980s, Mayweather lived in the Hiram Square neighborhood of [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]], where his mother had relatives.<ref>Politi, Steve. [http://www.nj.com/boxing-news/index.ssf/2015/05/floyd_mayweather_is_a_jersey_g.html \"Is Floyd Mayweather a Jersey guy? Tracing his roots to a New Brunswick block\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], May 1, 2015. Accessed August 29, 2017. \"Hiram Square in New Brunswick as it looked in the mid 1970s. Floyd Mayweather lived on the street with his mother in the mid 1980s.\"</ref> He later said, \"When I was about eight or nine, I lived in [[New Jersey]] with my mother and we were seven deep in one bedroom and sometimes we didn't have electricity. When people see what I have now, they have no idea of where I came from and how I didn't have anything growing up.\"\n\nIt was common for the young Mayweather to come home from school and find used [[Hypodermic needle|heroin needles]] in his front yard.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://herdsay.com/floyd-mayweather/ |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. \u2013 Biography |publisher=HERDsay.com |accessdate=October 24, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150523120006/http://herdsay.com/floyd-mayweather/ |archive-date=May 23, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His mother was [[substance dependence|addicted to drugs]], and he had an aunt who died from [[AIDS]] because of her drug use. \"People don't know the hell I've been through,\" he says. The most time that his father spent with him was taking him to the gym to train and work on his boxing, according to Mayweather. \"I don't remember him ever taking me anywhere or doing anything that a father would do with a son, going to the park or to the movies or to get ice cream,\" he says. \"I always thought that he liked his daughter (Floyd's older sister) better than he liked me because she never got whippings and I got whippings all the time.\"\n\nMayweather's father contends that Floyd is not telling the truth about their early relationship. \"Even though his daddy did sell drugs, I didn't deprive my son,\" the elder Mayweather says. \"The drugs I sold, he was a part of it. He had plenty of food. He had the best clothes and I gave him money. He didn't want for anything. Anybody in Grand Rapids can tell you that I took care of my kids\".<ref name=\"Mayweather's life story\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2007/04/29/2007-04-29_stormy_mayweather.html |last=Smith|first=Tim|title=Stormy Mayweather |work=New York Daily News |date=April 30, 2007 |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> Floyd Sr. says he did all of his hustling at night and spent his days with his son, taking him to the gym and training him to be a boxer. \"If it wasn't for me he wouldn't be where he is today,\" he maintains.\n\n\"I basically raised myself,\" Mayweather says. \"My grandmother did what she could. When she got mad at me I'd go to my mom's house. My life was ups and downs.\" His father says he knows how much pain his [[incarceration]] caused his son, but insists he did the best he could. \"I sent him to live with his grandmother,\" he says. \"It wasn't like I left him with strangers.\" In the absence of his father, boxing became an outlet for Mayweather.<ref name=\"Mayweather's life story\" /> As the elder Mayweather served his time, his son put all of his energy into boxing and dropped out of high school. \"I knew that I was going to have to try to take care of my mom and I made the decision that school wasn't that important at the time and I was going to have to box to earn a living,\" he said.<ref name=\"Mayweather's life story\" />\n\n==Amateur boxing career==\nMayweather had an amateur record of 84\u20138<ref>[http://translate.google.com/translate?&sl=es&u=http://www.geocities.ws/pedrinet/mayweather.html&prev=/search%3Fq%3Dwww.geocities.ws/pedrinet/mayweather.html%26client%3Dfirefox-a%26hs%3DF1u%26rls%3Dorg.mozilla:en-US:official] GFAX. Retrieved April 16, 2006.</ref> and won national [[Golden Gloves]] championships in 1993 (at 106&nbsp;[[Pound (mass)|lb]]), 1994 (at 114&nbsp;lb), and 1996 (at 125&nbsp;lb).<ref>[http://www.hbo.com/boxing/fighters/mayweather/index.shtml HBO: Boxing \u2013 Floyd Mayweather Jr.] [[HBO]]. Retrieved January 7, 2006.</ref> He was nicknamed \"Pretty Boy\" by his amateur teammates because he had relatively few scars, a result of the [[Boxing styles and technique#Defense|defensive techniques]] that his father and uncle (Roger Mayweather) had taught him.<ref>Schulberg, Benn. [http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2879/floyd-mayweather-born-pretty-boy/ \"Floyd Mayweather Jr. Born to be a Pretty Boy.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506065349/http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2879/floyd-mayweather-born-pretty-boy/ |date=May 6, 2006 }} November 19, 2005. ''The Sweet Science''. Retrieved April 12, 2006.</ref> In his orthodox defensive stance Mayweather often utilizes the [[shoulder roll]], an old-school boxing technique in which the right hand is held normally (or slightly higher than normal), the left hand is down around the [[midsection]] and the lead [[shoulder]] is raised high on the [[cheek]] in order to cover the [[chin]] and block punches. The right hand (as in the [[orthodox stance]]) is used as it normally would be: to block punches coming from the other side, such as left [[Hook (boxing)|hooks]]. From this stance Mayweather blocks, slips and deflects most of his opponents' punches (even when cornered) by twisting left and right to the rhythm of their punches.<ref>Coleman, Steve. [http://m-base.com/sweet_science.html \"The Sweet Science: Floyd Mayweather and Improvised Modalities of Rhythm.\"] December 1, 2003. ''Sudden Thoughts''. Retrieved April 22, 2006.</ref>\n\n===1996 Olympics===\nAt the [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]], Mayweather won a [[Boxing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Featherweight|bronze medal]] by reaching the semi-finals of the [[featherweight]] (57-[[kilogram|kg]])<ref>Olympic weight classes use kilograms instead of pounds. 57 kg \u2248 125.66 lb</ref> division.\n\nIn the first fight, Mayweather led 10\u20131 on points over [[Bakhtiyar Tileganov]] of [[Kazakhstan]], before winning when the fight was stopped. In the second fight, Mayweather outpointed [[Artur Gevorgyan]] of [[Armenia]] 16\u20133. In the quarterfinals, the 19-year-old Mayweather narrowly defeated 22-year-old [[Lorenzo Aragon]] of [[Cuba]] in an all-action bout to win 12\u201311, becoming the first U.S boxer to defeat a Cuban in 20 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadastarboxing.com/Fighters/floyd-mayweather-profile.htm |title=Floyd Mayweather: Profile and Bio |publisher=Canadastar Boxing |accessdate=November 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028165550/http://www.canadastarboxing.com/Fighters/floyd-mayweather-profile.htm |archivedate=October 28, 2011  }}</ref> The last time this occurred was the [[1976 Summer Olympics]], when the U.S Olympic boxing team captured five gold medals; among the recipients was Sugar Ray Leonard. In his semifinal bout against eventual [[silver medal]]ist [[Serafim Todorov]] of [[Bulgaria]], Mayweather lost by a controversial decision (similar to [[Roy Jones Jr.]]'s highly controversial [[Roy Jones Jr.#Amateur career|decision loss]] to [[Park Si-hun]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Cyphers |first=Luke |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/1996-08-03/sports/18015724_1_floyd-mayweather-emil-jetchev-judges |title=U.s. Protests Boxing; Judge Quits |work=New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=August 3, 1996 |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> [[Referee (boxing)|Referee]] Hamad Hafaz Shouman of [[Egypt]] mistakenly raised Mayweather's hand (thinking he had won), while the decision was announced giving the bout to the Bulgarian.<ref name=\"google6880\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UysvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mDMDAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather%20serafim%20todorov&pg=6880%2C9201988|title= Robbed? Mayweather goes home with controversial loss |publisher= |date=August 4, 1996 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. team filed a protest over the Mayweather bout, claiming the [[Boxing judge|judges]] were intimidated by Bulgaria's Emil Jetchev (head of the boxing officials) into favoring the Bulgarian Todorov by a 10\u20139 decision in the 125-pound semifinal bout. Three of Jetchev's countrymen were in [[gold medal]] bouts. Judge Bill Waeckerle (one of the four [[U.S.]] judges working the games for the [[International Boxing Association (amateur)|International Amateur Boxing Federation]]) resigned as [[Olympic Games]] and federation judge after Mayweather lost the decision, which was loudly booed by the crowd at the [[Alexander Memorial Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LiRUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SY4DAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather%20serafim%20todorov&pg=6746%2C546842|title=Judge quits in protest of 'incompetent' scoring; Mayweather loses controversial decision |publisher= |date=August 3, 1996 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YWwVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TwsEAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather%20serafim%20todorov&pg=3597%2C558074|title=US boxing judge resigns; hits corruption in AIBA |publisher= |date=August 4, 1996 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> \"I refuse to be part of an organization that continues to conduct its officiating in this manner\", Waeckerle wrote in his letter of resignation to federation president [[Anwar Chowdhry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7LsaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rjsEAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather&pg=1979%2C2373356|title=''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'' |publisher= |date=August 2, 1996 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the official protest U.S. team manager Gerald Smith said Mayweather landed punches that were not counted, while Todorov was awarded points without landing a [[Punch (combat)|punch]].<ref name=\"nytimes1996\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/03/sports/one-us-boxer-left-standing-for-the-finals.html | work=The New York Times | first=Mike | last=Wise | title=One U.S. Boxer Left Standing For the Finals | date=August 3, 1996}}</ref> \"The judging was totally incompetent,\" Waeckerle said. The judges failed to impose a mandatory two-point deduction against Todorov after he was warned five times by the referee for [[Slapping (strike)|slapping]].<ref name=\"google6880\"/>\n\"Everybody knows Floyd Mayweather is the gold-medal favorite at 57 kilograms,\" Mayweather said afterward. \"In America, it's known as 125 pounds. You know and I know I wasn't getting hit. They say he's the world champion. Now you all know who the real world champion is.\"<ref name=\"nytimes1996\"/>\n\n'''Featherweight Olympic qualification'''\n*Defeated William Jenkins RSC/TKO-3\n*Defeated James Baker RSCH/TKO-1\n*Lost to [[Augie Sanchez]] PTS (11\u201312)\n*Defeated Carlos Navarro PTS (31\u201311)\n*Defeated Augie Sanchez PTS (12\u20138) in the box-offs\n*Defeated Augie Sanchez PTS (20\u201310) in the box-offs\n\n'''Olympic results'''\n*Defeated Bakhtiyar Tileganov (Kazakhstan) RSCI/TKO-2\n*Defeated Artur Gevorgyan (Armenia) PTS (16\u20133)\n*Defeated Lorenzo Aragon (Cuba) PTS (12\u201311)\n*Lost to [[Serafim Todorov]] (Bulgaria) PTS (9\u201310)*\n:<nowiki>*</nowiki>''Decision was protested unsuccessfully by the U.S. team''\n\n==Professional boxing career==\n\n===Super featherweight===\nMayweather won his first professional bout on October 11, 1996, when he knocked out fellow newcomer Roberto Apodaca in Round 2. Mayweather's trainer at the time was his uncle, Roger Mayweather; his father was still imprisoned after his conviction for [[Illegal drug trade#Trafficking and distribution|illegal drug trafficking]] in 1993. The latter took over as his son's trainer when he was released from prison (after Mayweather Jr.'s 14th fight\u2014a second-round knockout of Sam Girard).<ref>Pierce, Ben. [http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news/pierce2208.php \"Floyd Mayweather Sr.: Father, son and holy cow!\"] August 22, 2002. ''East Side Boxing''. Retrieved April 17, 2006.</ref> From 1996 to early 1998, Mayweather won most of his fights by knockout or TKO.\n\nEarly in his pro career, Mayweather received praise from all corners of the boxing world and was touted as a pugilistic prodigy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2000-08-23/sports/18151892_1_mayweather-kery-davis-rosendo-alvarez |title=Hbo Reaches Out To Mayweather |work=New York Daily News  |date=August 23, 2000 |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> During his fight with Tony Duran<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php?title=Fight:11648 |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Tony Duran |work=Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> the [[ESPN]] commentator remarked, \"[[Emmanuel Steward]] was quoted as saying there have been very few who have been more talented than this kid. He will probably win two or three world championships; I think he will go on to be the best ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lt03rJUzV4s |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Tony Duran |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> IBHOF trainer and commentator [[Gil Clancy]] commented before Mayweather's ninth professional fight (against Jesus Chavez), \"I thought that Floyd Mayweather was the outstanding pro prospect in the entire [[Olympic games]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_pg1HM3bJyA |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Jesus Chavez Pt.1 (1997) |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Hernandez====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Floyd Mayweather vs. Genaro Hern\u00e1ndez.jpg|thumb|right|Mayweather with his hand raised after defeating Genaro Hernandez, to capture his first world title, in 1998]] -->\nIn 1998, within two years of entering [[professional boxing]], Mayweather decisively won his first world title (the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[super featherweight]] (130&nbsp;lb) championship) with an eighth-round [[technical knockout]] of ''The Ring'' world #1-ranked super featherweight [[Genaro Hern\u00e1ndez]] after his opponent's [[cornerman]] stopped the fight. It was Hern\u00e1ndez' first defeat in that weight class; he said after the fight, \"He defeated me, he is quick, smart and I always knew he had the speed. I give him respect. He is a true champ\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nFZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uRQEAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather&pg=6569%2C3999392|title=Floyd takes junior title in style |publisher= |date=October 5, 1998 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWith Mayweather's win he became lineal champion of the division; Genaro Hern\u00e1ndez had previously beaten [[Azumah Nelson]], whose dominance of the super-featherweight division had prompted boxing publications to give him the vacant lineal championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/jrlight.htm|title=The Lineal Junior Lightweight Champions|publisher=The Cyber Boxing Zone Encyclopedia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/forums/view.php?pg=pound/| last=Rold|first=Cliff|work=BoxingScene|title=BoxingScene's Pound for Pound Top Ten|quote=Floyd Mayweather (41\u20130, 25 KO) Age: 34 Lineal World Championships: World Jr. Lightweight (1998\u20132002, 8 Defenses); World Lightweight (2002\u20132004, 3 Defenses); World Welterweight (2006\u201308, 1 Defense) |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> ''The Ring'' stopped awarding belts to world champions in the 1990s, but began again in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/about |title=About the Ring &#124; RingTV |publisher=Ringtv.craveonline.com |date=February 15, 1922 |accessdate=November 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028050328/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/about |archivedate=October 28, 2011  }}</ref> Nelson won his lineal status during the 1990s; therefore, ''The Ring's'' vacant title was awarded neither to him, Hern\u00e1ndez, nor Mayweather (although Mayweather was ''The Ring's'' #1-ranked super featherweight).\n\nMayweather became the first 1996 U.S. Olympian to win a world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php?title=Fight:12847 |title=Genaro Hernandez vs. Floyd Mayweather Jr. \u2013 Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Following his victory Mayweather's promoter [[Bob Arum]] said, \"We believe in our heart of hearts that Floyd Mayweather is the successor in a line that starts with [[Sugar Ray Robinson|Ray Robinson]], goes to [[Muhammad Ali]], then Sugar Ray Leonard...We believe that he epitomizes that style of fighting\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/18/sports/boxing-mayweather-s-father-is-his-biggest-booster.html |title=BOXING; Mayweather's Father Is His Biggest Booster \u2013 Page 2 \u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=December 18, 1998 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |first=Timothy W. |last=Smith}}</ref> After capturing the title Mayweather defended it against contender [[Angel Manfredy]] with a TKO in round two, giving Manfredy his first defeat in four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_1ZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xRQEAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather&pg=7003%2C2756956|title=Mayweather stops Manfredy to retain title |publisher= |date=December 21, 1998 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 1998 Mayweather was ranked by ''The Ring'' as the #8-ranked pound-for-pound best boxer in the world,<ref name=\"ringlivesports1\">{{cite web |author=RingLive Sports |url=http://www.ringlivesports.info/boxing/ring-magazine-awards/pound-for-pound-history/ |title=Pound for Pound History |publisher=Ringlivesports.info |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130218074927/http://www.ringlivesports.info/boxing/ring-magazine-awards/pound-for-pound-history/ |archivedate=February 18, 2013  }}</ref> and became one of the youngest recipients of ''The Ring's'' [[Ring Magazine fighters of the year#1990s|Fighter of the Year]] award (21, the same age Sugar Ray Robinson and Muhammad Ali were when winning their first awards).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LPZlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QYkNAAAAIBAJ&dq=sugar%20ray%20robinson%20the%20ring%20fighter%20of%20the%20year&pg=1480%2C5017761|title=Sugar Tops Poll |publisher= |date=December 26, 1942 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=evEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ndUEAAAAIBAJ&dq=cassius%20clay%20fighter%20of%20the%20year&pg=2444%2C3256645|title=Clay Is Named Fighter Of The Year |publisher= |date=December 28, 1993 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\nIn 1999, Mayweather continued his domination of the super featherweight division by defending his title three more times. The second defense of his title was against the [[Argentine]] Carlos Rios, which he won in a [[unanimous decision]]. Mayweather, fighting past the eighth round for only the third time in his career, won on the judges' scoring 120\u2013110, 119\u2013108, and 120\u2013109.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=B8hGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5fMMAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather%20carlos%20rios&pg=4854%2C2532505|title=WBC 130-pound champ Mayweather defeats Rios |publisher= |date=February 18, 1999 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMayweather's third title defense was against [[Justin Juuko]], which he won via [[knockout]] in the ninth round. Juuko could not beat the count of 10 by referee [[Mitch Halpern]], and the fight ended in Mayweather's favor 80 seconds into that (the ninth) round.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/23/sports/boxing-de-la-hoya-knocks-out-carr-in-11th.html |title=BOXING; De La Hoya Knocks Out Carr in 11th |work=The New York Times |date=May 23, 1999 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |first=Timothy W. |last=Smith}}</ref> His final title defense in 1999 was against [[Carlos Gerena]], with Mayweather winning in a seventh-round [[referee technical decision]] (RTD). Mayweather said after the fight, \"I want to show the world that along with [[Oscar De La Hoya]] and [[Roy Jones Jr.]], I'm the best fighter in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GU5WAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5usDAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather&pg=6003%2C3329324|title=Mayweather dominates Gerena |publisher=Google |date=September 13, 1999 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> This dominance did not go unnoticed in the boxing world; by the end of the year, the 22-year-old Mayweather was ranked ''The Ring's'' #2 pound-for-pound best boxer in the world (behind Roy Jones Jr.).<ref name=\"ringlivesports1\"/>\n\nBefore making the fifth successful defense of his title against former WBC Featherweight Champion [[Gregorio Vargas]] in early 2000, Mayweather fired his father as his manager and replaced him with [[James Prince]]. A few months after the fight, the rift between father and son grew when Mayweather also fired the elder Mayweather as his trainer.<ref>Iole, Kevin. [http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2000/May-17-Wed-2000/sports/13592910.html \"Dinner spat widens Mayweather family rift.\"] May 17, 2000. ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]''. Retrieved April 17, 2006.</ref> In a 2004 interview Mayweather said that although he loves his father, he had a better chemistry with Roger because his father had put too much pressure on him to be perfect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inthiscornertv.com/pages/1/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061216081510/http://www.inthiscornertv.com/pages/1/index.htm |archivedate=December 16, 2006  }}</ref> Mayweather, in his fifth title defense, won a near-shutout over \"Goyo\" Vargas in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]]. During the 10th round, when Mayweather overheard [[HBO]] announcer [[Jim Lampley]] say that the champ had switched to a [[southpaw]] stance for the second time in the bout he leaned ringside and said \"It was the third time\". After a six-month layoff, Mayweather was still elusive. During the sixth round, Mayweather dropped Vargas with a hook to the [[ribs]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Hoffer, Richard |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1018780/1/index.htm |title=Boxing \u2013 03.27.00 \u2013 SI Vault |work=Sports Illustrated |date=March 27, 2000 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> and cruised to a unanimous decision.\n\nRoger Mayweather returned to his role as his nephew's trainer for his next bout; a non-title [[lightweight]] fight against [[Emanuel Burton]], which Mayweather won in a ninth-round technical knockout.\n\n====Mayweather vs. Corrales====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Maywether Corrales.jpg|200px|thumb|right|HBO poster Mayweather-Corrales Super Featherweight championship bout]] -->\n\nIn one of the more definitive and memorable fights of his career Mayweather fought the hard-hitting, former [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] super-featherweight champion [[Diego Corrales]] (33\u20130, with 27 KOs). Coming into the bout Mayweather and Corrales were undefeated, and neither fighter had touched the canvas. Mayweather was ''The Ring's'' #2-ranked super featherweight in the world (and #7 pound-for-pound), while Corrales was the #1-ranked super featherweight in the world and #5 pound-for-pound.<ref name=\"ringlivesports1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/The_Ring_Magazine%27s_Annual_Ratings:_Junior_Lightweight--2000s |title=The Ring Magazine's Annual Ratings: Junior Lightweight-2000s \u2013 Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |date=February 13, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Before the fight was announced Mayweather had stated he wanted to fight Corrales, who was facing jail time for allegedly beating his pregnant wife. \"I want Diego because I'm doing it for all the battered women across [[United States|America]]\", Mayweather said. \"Just like he beat that woman, I'm going to beat him\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2000-10-21/sports/18152193_1_roger-mayweather-fighter-pound-for-pound-rap-music-producer-james-prince |title=Floyd No Longer Fighting Mad \u2013 New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=October 21, 2000 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhile both fighters were the same age (23), Corrales had several physical advantages over Mayweather: two inches in height, an inch in reach and (despite both arriving at the official weight-in at the 130-lb super-featherweight limit) unofficially 146&nbsp;lbs, versus Mayweather's 136{{sfrac|1|2}} lbs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tYgDG8JZ2rA |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Diego Corrales Pt.1 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> In the bout, Mayweather won every round and knocked down Corrales five times (three times in round 7 and twice in round 10). After the fifth knockdown, Corrales' cornermen climbed onto the apron and stopped the fight, thereby establishing Mayweather as a claimant to boxing's mythical pound-for-pound title. At the time of the stoppage Mayweather was ahead on the scorecards, leading by 89\u201379, 90\u201379, and 90\u201378.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxrec.com/boxer_display.php?boxer_id%3D000352 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060424103955/http://www.boxrec.com/boxer_display.php?boxer_id=000352 |archivedate=April 24, 2006  }}</ref> Throughout the fight, HBO commentators analyzed Mayweather. [[Larry Merchant]] stated, \"Mayweather fights in a tradition of [[boxing]] and quick handedness that goes back in [[Michigan]], all the way to fighters like Sugar Ray Robinson\". [[Harold Lederman]] remarked, <blockquote>Jim (Lampley), I gotta tell ya, I'm terribly impressed, I don't think I've seen an exhibition of boxing like this since [[Willie Pep]], this kid is unbelievable, great legs, great speed, unbelievable ring-generalship. I mean he's got tremendous presence in that ring, Floyd Mayweather knows where he is, every minute of this fight...</blockquote>\n\nCorrales landed 60 of 205 punches, and landed no more than nine punches in a single round. Mayweather landed 220 of 414 punches.<ref name=\"cbsnews2001\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2001/01/20/sports/main265864.shtml |title=Mayweather Mauls Corrales |publisher=CBS News |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Corrales was unable to land any clean shots, as he stalked Mayweather through the early rounds. He landed an average of six punches a round, according to [[CompuBox]] stats \u2013 the only time that a fighter has registered single digits in the 20 years CompuBox has been tracking punch statistics.<ref name=\"nydailynews2001\">{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2001-01-21/sports/18176367_1_diego-corrales-ray-woods-speed |title=Mayweather Storms Foe \u2013 New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=January 21, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fight Mayweather remarked, \"I would like to fight [[Naseem Hamed|Prince Naseem]] (Hamed), hopefully we can meet at 128 (lbs) or he can come up to 130 (lbs), we can fight or I can fight the winner of [[Joel Casamayor|Casamayor]]...\" \"Prince Naseem isn't going to fight you,\" intervened HBO commentator Larry Merchant; who then chuckled and added: \"after he saw this, it ain't gonna happen\".\n\"I really want to fight Prince Naseem...\" Mayweather continued, \"but hopefully I can face the winner of Casamayor (vs.) [[Acelino Freitas|Freitas]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ykG4Xnk85_E |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Diego Corrales Pt.7 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Although neither fight materialised, Mayweather's opponent Diego Corrales would later hand Freitas (the winner of the Casamayor vs. Freitas fight) his first professional defeat and defeat Casamayor via controversial decision in a rematch of their first bout. Afterwards, Bob Arum was ecstatic about his new star. \"Better than [[Sugar Ray Leonard]]\", he asserted. \"And did you see him at those press conferences...?\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Hoffer, Richard |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142966/1/index.htm |title=Boxing \u2013 01.29.01 \u2013 SI Vault |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 29, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe fight was met with acclaim in the boxing world and sports in general. [[CBS]] said, \"Floyd Mayweather Jr.'s speed was dazzling. His power was unexpected\"<ref name=\"cbsnews2001\"/> and the [[BBC]] reported on \"... a near flawless performance...\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/1129655.stm |title=BBC Sport&#124; Other Sports &#124; Mayweather impresses with Corrales win |publisher=BBC News |date=January 21, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' reported that \"Floyd Mayweather Jr., displaying blazing speed and punishing power...\"<ref name=\"nydailynews2001\"/> and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported \"... a fistic masterpiece\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Hoffer, Richard |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142966/index.htm |title=Boxing \u2013 01.29.01 \u2013 SI Vault |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 29, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2001, boxing trainer [[Eddie Futch]] died at age 90. Tim Smith of the New York ''Daily News'' remembered an encounter with the trainer in an article.\n\n<blockquote>One of the last times I saw Futch was before the Floyd Mayweather Jr.\u2013Diego Corrales [[junior lightweight]] title bout in Vegas. Futch was talking about how much he admired Mayweather's style, how Mayweather was such a beautiful boxer, able to slip along the ropes and avoid punches. Corrales said he was going to neutralize Mayweather's hand speed by hitting Mayweather on the arms. \"I guess he thinks he's going to stand there and let him hit him on the arms all night,\" said Futch, who correctly predicted that Mayweather would completely dismantle Corrales in a defensive masterpiece. Futch had a way of cutting to the heart of a matter. I don't know anyone in boxing who won't miss him. I don't know anyone in boxing that can take his place.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2001-10-11/sports/18353711_1_eddie-futch-trainer-montell-griffin |title=Famed Trainer Futch Dies At 90 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |date=October 11, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn May 26, 2001, Mayweather, fighting in his hometown of Grand Rapids, pounded out a 12-round unanimous decision over future IBF super featherweight titleholder [[Carlos Hern\u00e1ndez (boxer)|Carlos Hern\u00e1ndez]] to retain his WBC super-featherweight title. Calling it \"one of the toughest nights of my career\", the 130-pound champion overcame injuries in both hands to improve his record to 26\u20130. \"He is a very, very tough fighter,\" Mayweather said of the challenger, whose record fell to 33\u20133\u20131. \"I'm disappointed in my performance.\" Mayweather suffered the first knockdown of his career when he hit Hern\u00e1ndez with a left hook in round six, which caused him sufficient pain that he dropped his injured left hand to the canvas. He wasn't hit, but was given a standing eight-count by the referee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/28/sports/plus-boxing-mayweather-wins-with-hands-hurt.html |title=Mayweather Wins With Hands Hurt |work=The New York Times |date=May 28, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMayweather's last fight in the super-featherweight division was against future super featherweight and lightweight titleholder [[Jes\u00fas Ch\u00e1vez]]. Ch\u00e1vez was the WBC's top-ranked contender<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aRQ0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KiEGAAAAIBAJ&dq=floyd%20mayweather%20jesus%20chavez&pg=1581%2C1245610|title=Mayweather stops Chavez after nine |publisher=Google |date=November 13, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> and came into the fight with a 31-bout winning streak. This was Mayweather's eighth defense of the WBC super-featherweight title, which he had held for more than three years. He won when Ch\u00e1vez's corner stopped the fight after round nine. Mayweather had such difficulty making weight for this fight that he did not eat for four days before the weigh-in.<ref>Curry, Chris. [http://www.eastsideboxing.com/MayweathervsChavez.html \"Floyd Mayweather Shows Chavez Boxing's Not So Pretty.\"] November 11, 2001. ''East Side Boxing''. Retrieved April 17, 2006.</ref> Ch\u00e1vez stated after the fight, \"He's [Mayweather] the champ! And now I become his number-one fan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGSUqmbLBv8 |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Jesus Chavez Pt.5 (2001) |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMayweather commented after the fight, \"Although it will take some time to make the match, I want to fight Kostya Tszyu\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Mee |first=Bob |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxingandmma/3016650/Boxing-Mayweather-to-move-onwards-and-upwards.html |title=Boxing: Mayweather to move onwards and upwards |publisher=Telegraph |date=November 11, 2001 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Tszyu, an [[Australians|Australian]]-based [[Russians|Russian]], by then had established himself as the best [[light welterweight]] in the world. Mayweather did not get a chance to fight Tszyu, but went on to fight [[Ricky Hatton]] (who defeated Tszyu and won his ''Ring'' light welterweight championship). By the end of 2001, Mayweather was still ranked ''The Ring'' #1 super featherweight and #5 best pound-for-pound boxer in the world.<ref name=\"ringlivesports2\">{{cite web |author=RingLive Sports |url=http://www.ringlivesports.info/boxing/ring-magazine-awards/pound-for-pound-history |title=Pound for Pound History |publisher=Ringlivesports.info |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130218080335/http://www.ringlivesports.info/boxing/ring-magazine-awards/pound-for-pound-history |archivedate=February 18, 2013  }}</ref>\n\n===Lightweight===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Castillo I====\nIn his first fight as a lightweight, Mayweather took on World Boxing Council (WBC) champion and ''The Ring'' #1-ranked lightweight [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Castillo]]. Despite both fighters officially meeting the 135-lb lightweight limit, Mayweather came to the ring weighing unofficially 138{{sfrac|1|2}} lbs to Castillo's 147{{sfrac|1|2}} lbs. He defeated Castillo, winning the WBC and vacant ''The Ring'' and lineal lightweight titles with a 12-round unanimous decision at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] before a crowd of 6,920. With Mayweather's win, he became the first lineal lightweight champion since Pernell Whitaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/light.htm|title=The Lineal Lightweight Champions|publisher=The Cyber Boxing Zone Encyclopedia}}</ref> Judges Jerry Roth and John Keane scored it 115\u2013111 and judge Anek Hongtongkam scored it 116\u2013111, a decision that was loudly booed by the pro-Castillo crowd. The [[Associated Press]] had Mayweather winning, 115\u2013111;<ref name=\"peninsulaclarion1\">{{cite web |url=http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/042102/spo_042102spo0130001.shtml |title=Mayweather wins WBC title |publisher=Peninsula Clarion |date=April 21, 2002 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930153756/http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/042102/spo_042102spo0130001.shtml |archive-date=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the New York ''Daily News'' scorecard also had Mayweather winning, 116\u2013112.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-04-21/sports/18194799_1_mayweather-jose-luis-castillo-vic-drakulich |title=It's Unanimous: Mayweather Wins \u2013 New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=April 21, 2002 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCastillo (45\u20135\u20131, 41 KOs) could not touch Mayweather in the first round, with Castillo throwing 27 punches and landing only three. After round one Larry Merchant pointed out, \"Mayweather made a comment in the corner about his left shoulder. We'll see if something's wrong with it, he seems to be rotating it, trying to keep it loose\". [[George Foreman]] noted likewise, adding \"'Massage my left shoulder', he (Mayweather) said, that's not a good sign\".<ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ov6xoYMfbI |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Jose Luis Castillo I Pt.2 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the first minute of the second round Castillo went down on a shot by Mayweather, which was ruled a slip by the referee. Later in the fight Harold Lederman alluded to it, saying \"By the way, that knockdown in the second round [is] extremely questionable, I thought Floyd did throw a left hook and this guy [Castillo] went down at the end of the hook but what you going to do, it's a judgement call by the referee, so it doesn't go as a 10\u20138 round...\"<ref name=\"youtube1\"/> Drakulich took a point from Castillo for hitting on the break in the eighth round after several warnings throughout the fight. With Castillo repeatedly hitting on the break, this led to a large number of his punches landing. George Foreman agreed with the decision (\"That's what you want a referee to do\"), although his counterpart Larry Merchant had an alternative view: \"I think this referee has been altogether too involved in the fight. Too officious\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9MFx8CkdccM |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Jose Luis Castillo I Pt.4 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Drakulich struck again in the ninth round, this time taking a point away from Mayweather for using his elbows. Mayweather won the fight by using his [[jab]] effectively and staying away from Castillo for much of the fight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/21/sports/plus-boxing-mayweather-wins-lightweight-title.html |title=Plus: Boxing \u2013 Mayweather Wins Lightweight Title \u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=April 21, 2002 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Having injured his left shoulder on the last day of training, he changed to a southpaw stance on several occasions to throw more right-handed punches.\n\nAt the end of the fight, Harold Lederman had Castillo winning 115\u2013111. ESPN's [[Max Kellerman]] disputed Lederman's scoring, writing in his boxing column: \"Harold Lederman, the (HBO) unofficial ringside television judge, gave the third round to Castillo, which I think demonstrates that Mayweather suffers from the same scoring syndrome that afflicted Pernell Whitaker. Mayweather is so seldom hit cleanly in his face, that when a clean shot is landed against him it registers all out of proportion in the observer's mind. Meanwhile, the three clean shots Mayweather just landed against his opponent do not make the same kind of impression\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://a.espncdn.com/boxing/columns/kellerman_max/1373403.html |title=ESPN.com: Boxing \u2013 Mayweather prevails among controversy |publisher=A.espncdn.com |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCompuBox statistics indicated that Castillo landed more overall punches and significantly more power shots over the course of the fight. Mayweather outscored Castillo in jabs thrown and landed. Lederman's scoring for this fight may be seen as inconsistent {{By whom|section=Discussion about whom|date=June 2019}}; in both [[Bernard Hopkins]] vs. [[Jermain Taylor]] fights Lederman had Taylor winning 115\u2013113, despite Hopkins landing more overall punches and significantly more power shots during both fights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Bernard_Hopkins_vs._Jermain_Taylor_(1st_meeting) |title=Bernard Hopkins vs. Jermain Taylor (1st meeting) \u2013 Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Jermain_Taylor_vs._Bernard_Hopkins_(2nd_meeting) |title=Jermain Taylor vs. Bernard Hopkins (2nd meeting) \u2013 Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Taylor threw and landed more jabs, however.\n\nIn the post-fight interview Mayweather said, \"My last training day, I hurt my [[rotator cuff]] in my left shoulder, so I couldn't use my jab the way I want to. My left wasn't as strong as I wanted it to be, but I didn't want to have no excuses, you know, like other champions, you know, when they get hurt they won't even show up to the fight. I get hurt I keep fighting, you know, I want to bring the fans a victory\".\n\n====Mayweather vs. Castillo II====\nDue to the closeness of their first bout, Mayweather accepted an immediate rematch with Jos\u00e9 Luis Castillo which took place on December 7, 2002. Before the rematch, Mayweather reiterated that he had torn his left rotator cuff two days before the first fight and could not throw a jab or a left hook. He had surgery following the controversial decision over Castillo, and said his shoulder had fully healed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Tim |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2002-12-07/sports/18203766_1_mayweather-hbo-deal-james-prince |title=Mayweather Picks Fight With Press \u2013 New York Daily News |publisher=Articles.nydailynews.com |date=December 7, 2002 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe smaller Mayweather was again outweighed by Castillo on the night of the fight; Castillo weighed 147&nbsp;lbs, to Mayweather's 138.<ref name=\"autogenerated2002\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/boxing/news/2002/12/07/mayweather_castillo_ap/ |publisher=CNN |title=Mayweather outpoints Castillo to keep title belt |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214062521/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/boxing/news/2002/12/07/mayweather_castillo_ap/ |archivedate=February 14, 2009 }}</ref> In the rematch Mayweather used his footwork, combinations and jab to earn another unanimous decision. There were no knockdowns or notable exchanges in the fight; the judgment was close, with Mayweather winning 115\u2013113 on two scorecards and 116\u2013113 on a third. The Associated Press had Mayweather winning 116\u2013112;<ref name=\"autogenerated2002\"/> HBO unofficial scorer Harold Lederman and fellow analyst Larry Merchant both scored it 115\u2013113 for Mayweather.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Floyd_Mayweather_Jr._vs._Jose_Luis_Castillo_(2nd_meeting) |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Jose Luis Castillo (2nd meeting) \u2013 Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia |publisher=Boxrec.com |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn April 19, 2003, Mayweather defended his WBC lightweight title in a unanimous decision over [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] [[Victoriano Sosa]]. Mayweather (30\u20130) fought a tactically-sound 12-round bout against an aggressive Sosa (35\u20133\u20132). His next fight (on November 1 of the same year) was in his hometown of Grand Rapids against WBC #1-ranked contender [[Phillip N'dou]], whose record was 31\u20131 with 30 KOs. During the run-up to the fight [[Nelson Mandela]] invited N'dou to his office for a pep talk before his departure for the U.S., advising him to \"keep Mayweather on the outside with the jab, work the body and the head will become available\". South African president [[Thabo Mbeki]], in a note, said he had \"full confidence\" N'dou would put on a performance to make all South Africans proud and would return home with the WBC belt. When told of his opponent's high-level support Mayweather responded, \"Nelson Mandela's a great man, he's big in America, but Mandela can't get in there and fight for him\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Independent Newspapers Online |url=http://www.iol.co.za/sport/ndou-or-die-high-hopes-to-become-new-champ-1.530307 |title=Ndou or die \u2013 high hopes to become new champ \u2013 IOL Sport |publisher=IOL.co.za |date=October 31, 2003 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the fifth round, Mayweather connected with a series of [[Cross (boxing)|straight]] rights and lefts; when N'dou would not go down, Mayweather gave a little smile and continued the barrage. He dominated his opponent, before flooring him with a series of rights in the seventh round. N'dou got up on shaky legs, forcing a stoppage at 1:50. At times during the fight, Mayweather (in black trunks outlined with fur) seemed to toy with N'dou.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rafael |first=Dan |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/boxing/2003-11-02-mayweather-title_x.htm |title=WBC lightweight champ Mayweather KOs Ndou |work=USA Today |date=November 2, 2003 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> By the end of 2003, Mayweather was still ''The Ring's'' lightweight champion and the #5-ranked best pound-for-pound boxer in the world.<ref name=\"ringlivesports2\"/>\n\n===Light welterweight===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Corley====\nMayweather, at 27, made his 140-pound debut by defeating former titlist [[DeMarcus Corley|DeMarcus \"Chop Chop\" Corley]], knocking him down twice officially in rounds eight and ten, and scoring a unanimous decision of 119\u2013107, 119\u2013108, and 118\u2013108. The fight was billed as a WBC elimination bout, with the winner earning a shot at 140-pound champion [[Arturo Gatti]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A48930-2004May22.html |title=Mayweather's Debut At 140 Is Persuasive |work=The Washington Post |date=May 23, 2004 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> \"Mayweather can flat-out fight\", Corley's trainer [[Don Turner]] said. \"He's like magic. He makes you move into the punches.\"<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\"/> Shortly after this fight Mayweather would reach #1 on the ''[[USA Today]]'' pound-for-pound rankings, with [[middleweight]] champion Bernard Hopkins at #2.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rafael |first=Dan |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/boxing/2004-05-22-mayweather-corley_x.htm |title=Mayweather pounds Corley in win |work=USA Today |date=May 24, 2004 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Bruseles====\nOn January 22, 2005, Mayweather fought [[Henry Bruseles]] in another WBC elimination bout, outclassing Bruseles throughout the first seven rounds. In round eight, Mayweather knocked Bruseles down twice and the fight was stopped. Mayweather's victory made him the [[mandatory challenger]] for Gatti's WBC light welterweight championship.\n\n====Mayweather vs. Gatti====\n{{Main|Arturo Gatti vs. Floyd Mayweather}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Mayweather-Gatti.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Poster of Mayweather-Gatti billed as Thunder and Lightning]] -->\n\nThe [[pay-per-view]] fight between Mayweather and ''The Ring'' #1-ranked contender Arturo Gatti took place June 25, 2005 in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], where fans heavily supported Gatti. Before the fight Mayweather was confident, describing Gatti as \"a C+ fighter,\" \"a fake\" and \"a blown-up [[club fighter]]\".<ref>[http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=3873&more=1 \"Floyd Mayweather Conference Call Transcript.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060213221725/http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=3873&more=1 |date=February 13, 2006 }} May 16, 2005. ''East Side Boxing''. Retrieved April 23, 2006.</ref> Mayweather entered the ring being carried on a chariot to the song \"[[Another One Bites the Dust]]\".<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2094801 \"Mayweather's speed overwhelms Gatti\"]. ESPN. Retrieved December 28, 2012.</ref> Gatti entered the ring accompanied by the song \"[[Thunderstruck (song)|Thunderstruck]]\" and was momentarily frightened by the pyrotechnics exploding. Near the end of round one, Mayweather pushed Gatti's head down in close; Gatti broke, leaving himself vulnerable while Mayweather continued landing punches. Gatti turned to the referee to complain; Mayweather capitalised, sending Gatti to the canvas with more shots for what was scored a knockdown.<ref>Steinberg, Don. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2833471 \"Five key fights: Floyd Mayweather Jr.\"] ''ESPN.com''. Retrieved November 27, 2007.</ref> Throughout the next five rounds, the quicker Mayweather landed nearly every shot against Gatti, who had no offense with which to return fire. Gatti's corner stopped the fight after round six, giving Mayweather his third world title.\n\nIn the post-fight interview Mayweather praised Gatti, claiming that his pre-fight comments \"were just to sell tickets\". To many boxing experts, Mayweather's dominance of Gatti solidified his position as one of the best pound-for-pound fighters in the world.<ref>Upham, Paul. [http://www.secondsout.com/USA/news.cfm?ccs=229&cs=18444 \"The Boxing Experts on Floyd Mayweather Jr.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222507/http://www.secondsout.com/USA/news.cfm?ccs=229&cs=18444 |date=September 27, 2007 }} ''SecondsOut.com''. Retrieved January 28, 2006.</ref> CompuBox had Mayweather out-landing Gatti 168\u201341,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2303/mayweather-never-let-gatti-get-started |title=Mayweather Never Let Gatti Get Started |publisher=Thesweetscience.com |date=June 26, 2005 |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901195358/http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2303/mayweather-never-let-gatti-get-started |archivedate=September 1, 2009  }}</ref> with Gatti landing only 10 power punches (anything other than a jab).<ref>{{cite web|title=Arturo Gatti vs. Floyd Mayweather Jr.|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Arturo_Gatti_vs._Floyd_Mayweather_Jr.|work=Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia|publisher=Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia|accessdate=August 2, 2012|author=Boxrec Boxing Encyclopaedia|date=December 10, 2011}}</ref> Mayweather's fight with Gatti would be his last in the light-welterweight division; he would leave as ''The Ring'' #1-ranked contender, with Ricky Hatton as light-welterweight champion.\n\n===Welterweight===\nAfter his fight with Gatti, Mayweather moved up to the [[welterweight]] division. On November 19, 2005, Mayweather fought a non-title bout at {{convert|147|lb|abbr=on}} against welterweight [[Sharmba Mitchell]]. In round three, Mayweather knocked Mitchell down with a straight right hand to the head. In round six another straight right hand\u2014this one to Mitchell's body\u2014dropped Mitchell again, ending the fight.\n\n====Mayweather vs. Judah====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Zab Judah}}\nOn April 8, 2006, Mayweather defeated [[Zab Judah]] for the IBF welterweight title in a unanimous decision. Plans for the fight had been jeopardized after Judah lost the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]], WBC and ''The Ring'' Welterweight titles to [[Carlos Baldomir]] on January 7, 2006; however, Mayweather's and Judah's camps reworked the contract and decided that the fight would go on.<ref>Rafael, Dan. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2300340 \"Judah, Mayweather to fight in Vegas on April 8.\"] January 24, 2006. ''[[ESPN]].com''. Retrieved April 12, 2006.</ref> During the bout, Mayweather stayed calm during Judah's aggressive early rounds. He began to dominate Judah in round five, and the latter eventually bled. Late in the tenth round Judah hit Mayweather with a left hand that was clearly [[below the belt]], following with a right-handed [[rabbit punch]]. Referee [[Richard Steele (referee)|Richard Steele]] called time out with five seconds remaining in the round. Roger Mayweather entered the ring and approached Judah, but Steele restrained him; Judah's father (and trainer), [[Yoel Judah]], entered the ring as well. Mayweather remained in the neutral corner while the Judahs scuffled with Roger (and others who had entered the ring), until police and security restored order. Roger was ejected, and the fight continued for the scheduled 12 rounds. Mayweather won a unanimous decision by official scores of 116\u2013112, 117\u2013111, and 119\u2013109. CompuBox statistics showed him landing 188 punches, compared with 82 for Judah.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2402244 |title=Strong finish helps push Mayweather to victory \u2013 Boxing \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |date=April 8, 2006 |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFive days after the fight, the [[Nevada State Athletic Commission]] (NSAC) decided not to overturn the result of the bout; however, Roger Mayweather was fined $200,000 and suspended for one year.<ref>Vester, Mark. [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=3723 \"Mayweather Still Champ, Roger Not So Lucky.\"] April 13, 2006. ''BoxingScene.com''. Retrieved April 13, 2006.</ref> The suspension stipulated that Roger could train Mayweather in the gym, but could not work the corner during fights.<ref>Frauenheim, Norm. [http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/sports/articles/0417boxingnb0417.html \"Nevada deals big blow to Mayweather's uncle.\"] April 17, 2006. ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''. URL accessed May 3, 2006.</ref> On April 17, 2006, the IBF ordered a rematch between Mayweather and Judah; however, the NSAC suspended Judah for one year on May 8<ref>Rafael, Dan. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2438095 \"Judah and father fined, both lose license for year.\"] May 8, 2006. ''ESPN.com.'' URL accessed May 10, 2006.</ref> and Mayweather vacated the IBF title on June 20.\n\nAfter his fight with Judah it was reported that Mayweather rejected an $8&nbsp;million offer to fight [[Antonio Margarito]], citing his split with promoter Bob Arum as the reason.<ref>Rafael, Dan. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2420382 \"Mayweather turns down $8&nbsp;million to fight Margarito.\"] April 25, 2006. ''ESPN.com.'' URL accessed May 10, 2006.</ref> However, Oscar De la Hoya postponed his decision until 2007, leaving Mayweather to obtain [[Mayweather Promotions]] and choose his next opponent.<ref>Rafael, Dan. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2491946 \"De La Hoya won't fight Mayweather in fall, may retire.\"] June 19, 2006. ''ESPN.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2006.</ref> Mayweather considered moving up in weight again to fight [[light middleweight]] champion [[Cory Spinks]], but because of negative publicity and Spinks' impending mandatory defense of his title, he decided to face WBC and ''The Ring'' welterweight champion Carlos Baldomir on November 4, 2006 in Las Vegas.<ref>Rafael, Dan. [http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2549586 \"Mayweather, Baldomir to square off with title on line\"] August 14, 2006. ''ESPN.com.'.' Retrieved August 14, 2006.</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Baldomir====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Carlos Baldomir}}\nDespite having not lost in over eight years, Baldomir was an underdog in the fight. Mayweather defeated him for both titles in a unanimous decision. Ringside punch statistics showed Mayweather landing 199 of 458 punches, while Baldomir landed 79 of 670. Mayweather earned $8&nbsp;million for the fight; Baldomir was paid $1.6&nbsp;million, career earnings highs for each fighter at the time.\n\nDuring the fight Baldomir chased Mayweather, unable to land any meaningful shots but trying to be the busier fighter; Mayweather picked away with sharp jabs and hooks, cutting Baldomir over his left eye in the first round. This pattern continued throughout the fight; the defensive-minded Mayweather put on what many witnesses (and Mayweather himself) called a \"boxing clinic\" to take Baldomir's WBC, ''The Ring'' and lineal welterweight titles in a lopsided 12-round decision by scores of 120\u2013108, 120\u2013108, and 118\u2013110.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/welter.htm|title=The Lineal Welterweight Champs|publisher=The Cyber Boxing Zone Encyclopedia}}</ref> After the fight, Mayweather proposed a match with Oscar De La Hoya.\n\nWith Mayweather's win, he became the first fighter since [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]] to have captured ''The Ring'' titles in both the lightweight and welterweight divisions.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} He also captured his third lineal championship in as many weight classes (super featherweight, lightweight and welterweight), following in the footsteps of [[Henry Armstrong]] and Sugar Ray Leonard.\n\n===Light middleweight===\n\n====Mayweather vs. De La Hoya====\n{{main|Oscar De La Hoya vs. Floyd Mayweather}}\nMayweather's next match was the long-anticipated fight against six-division champion and WBC light-middleweight titleholder Oscar De La Hoya on May 5, 2007. De La Hoya's belt was on the line, which required Mayweather to move up in weight from 147 pounds to 154. However, Mayweather was outweighed by more than 10 pounds the night of the fight, coming in at only 150 pounds. Despite De La Hoya's insistence that money was not a factor, the Mayweather-De La Hoya bout set the record for most PPV buys for a boxing match with 2.7&nbsp;million households, breaking the previous record of 1.95&nbsp;million for [[Evander Holyfield-Mike Tyson II]]. About $120&nbsp;million in revenue was generated by the PPV, another record. Including percentages De La Hoya earned $58&nbsp;million for the bout, the highest purse ever for a fighter; the previous record was $35&nbsp;million, held by Tyson and Holyfield. Mayweather earned about $25&nbsp;million for the fight.<ref>Burt, Jason. [https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/davies-outburst-hangs-cloud-over-derbys-16360m-parade-450805.html \"Other glittering showdowns: Oscar de la Hoya v Floyd Mayweather\"] May 29, 2007. ''independent.co.uk''. Retrieved March 6, 2008.</ref>\n\nAt one time, Floyd Mayweather Sr. negotiated to train Oscar De La Hoya and be in his corner during the fight, but De La Hoya decided to train with [[Freddie Roach (boxing)|Freddie Roach]]. Mayweather won the fight by a split decision in 12 rounds, capturing the WBC title. However, many analysts and ringside observers felt Mayweather should have received a unanimous decision. During the early rounds De La Hoya had some success cutting off the ring, attempting to pound Mayweather on the inside. Despite his activity on the inside, however, many of De La Hoya's punches were ineffective and landed on Mayweather's arms or shoulders. By the middle of the fight, it was seen as an even bout by the announcers. Mayweather turned the tide in the middle and late rounds, often hitting De La Hoya at will. Official scorecards read 116\u2013112 (Mayweather), 115\u2013113 (Mayweather), and 115\u2013113 (De La Hoya). CompuBox had Mayweather out-landing De La Hoya 207\u2013122 in total punches and 134\u201382 in power punches, with better accuracy throughout the fight. After the bout Mayweather contemplated retirement, saying he had nothing left to prove in the boxing world.\n\n===Return to welterweight and retirement===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Hatton====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Ricky Hatton}}\n[[File:Mayweather Press Conference - 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Mayweather and Hatton during the press conference leading up to their much anticipated showdown, which would take place on December 8, 2007]]\nAfter his fight with De La Hoya, Mayweather decided to relinquish his WBC light-middleweight championship,<ref>[http://www.wbcboxing.com/WBCboxing/Portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=1909&docTipo=1&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC Floyd Mayweather WBC Emeritus Champion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208152247/http://www.wbcboxing.com/WBCboxing/Portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=1909&docTipo=1&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC |date=December 8, 2008 }}. [[World Boxing Council]] (July 4, 2007). Retrieved on May 17, 2009.</ref> retaining his welterweight title. On July 28, 2007, it was announced that Mayweather would come out of his brief retirement to fight ''The Ring'' light welterweight champion Ricky Hatton; the bout was promoted by De La Hoya's promotion company ([[Golden Boy Promotions]]) and Mayweather's Mayweather Promotions. The fight was entitled \"Undefeated\"; it took place December 8, 2007, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena, [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]], Nevada, the biggest welterweight showdown between two undefeated fighters since De La Hoya met F\u00e9lix Trinidad in 1999. During the run-up to their fight Mayweather claimed he was the greatest boxer ever: \"I respect what Robinson and Ali did for the sport. But I am the greatest and this is my time.\"\n\nMayweather controlled the fight from the beginning, knocking Hatton out in the 10th round to retain the welterweight championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://proxy.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=3147356 |title=Unbeaten Mayweather knocks out Hatton, retains title \u2013 Boxing \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |date=December 9, 2007 |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> Hatton suffered a cut over his right eye in round three; from that point, his pace and movement began to slow. In round six, Hatton lost a point for punching the back of Mayweather's head as he was draped over the ropes. During the tenth round, Hatton was caught by a checked left hook thrown from Mayweather's hip; after falling headfirst into the turnbuckle, he hit the floor. Hatton made it to his feet, but was dazed. Two more lefts in quick succession knocked Hatton down again, and referee Cortez stopped the fight at 1:35 of round ten.<ref>{{cite web |last=Swann |first=Michael |url=http://www.sportsline.com/boxing/story/10524248 |title=Mayweather becomes hero as Hatton loses his zero \u2013 Boxing |publisher=Sportsline.com |date=December 11, 2007 |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208232434/http://www.sportsline.com/boxing/story/10524248 |archivedate=December 8, 2008  }}</ref> Official scorecards read 88\u201382, 89\u201381, and 89\u201381 at the time of stoppage, all in favor of Mayweather.\n\nAfter the fight, Mayweather said that Hatton was one of his toughest, most tenacious opponents. Mayweather announced his retirement from boxing to concentrate on his promotional company, saying he wanted Hatton to be his first client.<ref>Rozenberg, Sammy. [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=11600 \"Mayweather Shocks, Knocks Hatton Out in Ten.\"] December 8, 2007. ''BoxingScene.com''. Retrieved December 8, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Comeback===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Marquez====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Juan Manuel Marquez}}\n[[File:Floyd Mayweather, Jr. vs. Juan Manuel M\u00e1rquez.jpg|thumb|left|Mayweather during his comeback bout against [[Juan Manuel M\u00e1rquez]], 2009]]\nOn May 2, 2009, it was confirmed that Mayweather was coming out of a 21-month retirement to fight ''The Ring'' lightweight champion and #2 pound-for-pound [[Juan Manuel M\u00e1rquez]], at a [[catch weight]] of 144&nbsp;lb on July 18 at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas on HBO PPV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=4125184 |title=Mayweather Jr. to fight again }}</ref> The fight was postponed due to a rib injury Mayweather received during training. HBO's sports series ''24/7'' was also rescheduled for August 29. The fight took place on September 19 in conjunction with [[Mexican Independence Day]], traditionally a big boxing weekend. During the official weigh-in for their 144&nbsp;lb bout, Mayweather failed to meet the weight limit at 146&nbsp;lb and was fined as a result.<ref>{{cite news|author=CBC Sports |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2009/09/18/sp-mayweather-marquez.html |title=Mayweather in weight flap for Marquez bout |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]  |date=September 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> However, it was later revealed that the contract was changed so that Mayweather could make weight within the welterweight limit of 140\u2013147&nbsp;lb as long as Marquez received a large guarantee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=4485941 |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. owes Juan Manual Marquez $600K after weighing two pounds overweight \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |date=September 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> Mayweather won a unanimous decision after 12 rounds in a lopsided fight; scorecards read 120\u2013107, 119\u2013108, and 118\u2013109. Marquez landed 12 percent of his total 583 punches, while Mayweather landed 59 percent of his 490 total punches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://compuboxonline.com/news.php?news=Mayweather-Marquez_Stats&news_id=9&start=0&category_id=7&parent_id=7&arcyear=Y&arcmonth=M |title=CompuBox Stats: Mayweather\u2013Marquez Stats |publisher=Compuboxonline.com |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725070911/http://compuboxonline.com/news.php?news=Mayweather-Marquez_Stats&news_id=9&start=0&category_id=7&parent_id=7&arcyear=Y&arcmonth=M |archivedate=July 25, 2011  }}</ref> This fight marked only the fifth time in boxing history that a non-[[heavyweight]] fight sold more than 1 million pay-per-view households, with HBO generating a revenue of approximately $52&nbsp;million. Four of the other fights featured Oscar De La Hoya as the main event, making this fight the one of two events where a non-heavyweight fight sold over 1&nbsp;million PPVs without Oscar De La Hoya. The other fight was [[Manny Pacquiao]] versus [[Miguel Cotto]], which sold 1.25&nbsp;million PPVs.<ref>{{cite web|author=Satterfield, Lem |url=http://boxing.fanhouse.com/2009/11/19/working-pacquiao-cotto-just-below-1-5-million/ |title=Pacquiao-Cotto PPV Numbers Rolling in, Nearing 1.5M Buys |publisher=Boxing FanHouse |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Mosley====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Shane Mosley}}\nNegotiations for a proposed match between Mayweather and ''The Ring'' #3 pound-for-pound [[Shane Mosley]] began right after [[Andre Berto]] pulled out of his scheduled January 30 [[Undisputed champion|unification bout]] with Mosley due to the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=4837075 |title=In mourning from Haiti earthquake, Andre Berto withdraws from Shane Mosley bout \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |date=January 20, 2010 |accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> Both sides eventually agreed to fight on May 1, 2010, for Mosley's WBA super-welterweight title. It was later revealed that Mayweather refused to pay sanctioning fees required by the WBA, saying \"All belts do is collect dust\". However, the belt was only on the line for Mosley to defend against Mayweather.<ref>Boxing, The. (April 23, 2010) [http://www.badlefthook.com/2010/4/23/1440558/wba-belt-not-on-the-line-for WBA belt not on the line for Mosley-Mayweather]. Badlefthook.com. Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref> Both Mayweather and Mosley agreed to Olympic-style testing for this bout.<ref>[http://fightfan.com/2010/01/mayweather-vs-mosley-clash-a-strong-possibility-now/#more-9421 Mayweather vs. Mosley clash a strong possibility now \u00bb FightFan.com Boxing News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122151747/http://fightfan.com/2010/01/mayweather-vs-mosley-clash-a-strong-possibility-now/ |date=January 22, 2010 }}. Fightfan.com (January 18, 2010). Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://fightfan.com/2010/01/mosley-and-mayweather-agree-to-terms-for-may-1-clash/ Mosley and Mayweather agree to terms for May 1 clash! \u00bb FightFan.com Boxing News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412120009/http://fightfan.com/2010/01/mosley-and-mayweather-agree-to-terms-for-may-1-clash/ |date=April 12, 2010 }}. Fightfan.com (January 31, 2010). Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nMosley started the fight well, landing two solid right hands in round two which caused Mayweather's knees to buckle. Mayweather recovered well and went on to dominate the remainder of the fight, out-boxing Mosley and showing more aggression than in his previous recent fights. Mayweather eventually won a unanimous decision, with the judges scoring the fight 119\u2013109, 119\u2013109, and 118\u2013110. In round four CompuBox found Mosley throwing seven power punches without taking any, making Mayweather the second boxer (after Roy Jones Jr.) to go an entire round without being hit by a power punch. After the fight, president of Golden Boy Promotions Oscar De La Hoya stated that he believed Mayweather was the best in the game.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/box/blog/box_experts/post/de-la-hoya-says-money-calls-the-shots-for-a-pa?urn=box,238605 de la hoya says 'money' calls the shots for a Pacquiao fight]. Sports.yahoo.com. Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nThe fight was the second-bestselling non-heavyweight pay-per-view bout in boxing history, with 1.4&nbsp;million purchases. HBO reported that the fight generated $78.3&nbsp;million in revenue. After the bout Mayweather expressed interest in moving up in weight to capture a world title in six different weight classes, and to challenge newly crowned middleweight champion [[Sergio Gabriel Martinez|Sergio Martinez]].<ref>[http://boxing.fanhouse.com/2010/05/06/sergio-martinez-on-floyd-mayweather-fight-would-be-action-packe/ Sergio Martinez on Floyd Mayweather: Fight Would Be Action-Packed]. Boxing.fanhouse.com (May 6, 2010). Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n====Negotiations with Manny Pacquiao====\n{{See also|Mayweather vs. Pacquiao}}\nOn December 5, 2009, ESPN reported that [[Octuple champion|eight-division world champion]] Manny Pacquiao signed a contract to fight Mayweather on March 13, 2010. Shortly afterward, Pacquiao denied ever signing a contract to fight Mayweather, telling ''[[FanHouse]]'', \"There are still some things that need to be negotiated.\"<ref name=\"timeline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fighthype.com/pages/mayweather-pacquiao-negotiations-timeline-1.html |title=Source:Mayweather-Pacquiao Negotiations Timeline Part 1 |publisher=Fighthype.com |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Yahoo! Sports]]'', an eight-page contract was sent on December 11, 2009, by Golden Boy Promotions on behalf of Mayweather to [[Top Rank]], representing Pacquiao, that proposed a 50\u201350 financial split between the sides for a fight to take place on March 13, 2010.\n\nThe eight-page agreement was so detailed that it indicated which of the two fighters would step onto the scale first at the weigh-in (Pacquiao), who would walk to the ring first (Pacquiao), who would be introduced first (Mayweather) and who had first choice of the locker room (Mayweather). It detailed that the bout would have been on [[HBO]] [[Pay-Per-View]] at a cost of $59.95. Billing was to be \"Mayweather vs. Pacquiao, presented by Top Rank, Golden Boy Promotions, Mayweather Promotions and M-P Promotions in association with [approved sponsors and the site].\" The contract also called for both fighters to submit to [[Olympic Games|Olympic]]-style [[drug test]]ing.\n\nA Mayweather-Pacquiao bout at that time was expected to be the largest-grossing fight in history, in which total revenues could reach $300 million. Experts predicted the fight would sell between 2.5 million and 3 million pay-per-views in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/boxing--floyd-mayweather-and-manny-pacquiao-nearly-agreed-to-a-2010-fight.html |title=Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao nearly agreed to a 2010 fight, documents show |publisher=Yahoo!Sports |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a video titled \"Boxing Legend Freddie Roach Updates Us On Pacquiao\" uploaded to [[YouTube]] on December 11, 2009, Pacquiao's trainer, Freddie Roach, revealed the first hint about Mayweather's request for Olympic-style drug testing, telling roving reporter Elie Seckbach, \"I hear negotiations are a little shady. Schaefer and them are unhappy about something. They want Olympic-style drug testing. I said, 'Yeah, no problem.' I said, 'Whatever you want.' Since we accepted that, now they're running scared again.\"<ref name=\"roach-updates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jGd8r7G7Mxo|title=Boxing Legend Freddie Roach Updates Us On Pacquiao|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=November 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2009, Pacquiao's adviser, Michael Koncz, said Mayweather's request for Olympic-style drug testing was a laughing matter and they had no concerns whatsoever about it. \"Our reaction is, 'So what?' We know Manny doesn't take any illegal drugs or anything. And none of this is getting under Manny's skin or anything. I'm here with Manny, and to him, it's like a joke. It's a laughing matter,\" said Koncz.\n\nAfter reports had surfaced that both parties had agreed to all terms, Golden Boy Promotions released a press release on December 22, 2009, revealing that Pacquiao was unwilling to comply with the Olympic-style drug testing requested by Team Mayweather. The following day, Bob Arum, Top Rank founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]], declared the fight was off and Pacquiao would be facing a different opponent: <blockquote>We appeased Mayweather by agreeing to a urine analysis at any time, and blood testing before the press conference and after the fight. Mayweather pressed for blood testing even up to the weigh-in. He knew that Manny gets freaked out when his blood gets taken and feels that it weakens him. This is just harassment and, to me, just signaled that he didn't want the fight.</blockquote> Arum told David Mayo of the [[The Grand Rapids Press|''Grand Rapids Press'']].\n\nNot long after declaring that the fight was off, Arum had a change of heart and offered Mayweather a 24-hour take-it-or-leave-it deadline to accept Team Pacquiao's terms for drug testing. Top Rank sent out a press release explaining their position on Mayweather's request for random Olympic-style drug testing. In it, Arum said Pacquiao was willing to submit to as many random urine tests requested, but as far as random blood tests were concerned, he was only willing to subject himself to 3 tests\u2014one in January, one 30 days from the bout (no later than February 13) and one immediately after the fight: <blockquote>Let's be very clear on the real issues we differ on. It's not about being tested....It's about who does the testing and the scheduling of the procedures....The major issue related to the testing rests with which independent agency will administer these tests. The [[United States Anti-Doping Agency]] (USADA) cannot do it because they will not amend its procedures to accommodate the blood testing schedule we have outlined. USADA, under its guidelines, would have the right to administer random blood tests as many times as they want up to weigh-in day and that is ludicrous.</blockquote>\n\nFreddie Roach told Lance Pugmire of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' on December 22 that he would prefer for Pacquiao to give his final blood sample a week before the bout and no later than 72 hours before.\n\nOn December 28, 2009, video from an episode of HBO's ''[[Ricky Hatton vs. Manny Pacquiao|Pacquiao-Hatton:]] 24/7'' surfaced on the internet showing Pacquiao giving blood in the weeks leading up to his May 2, 2009, bout with Ricky Hatton. Documents confirmed that the video was recorded on April 8, 2009, 24 days prior to the fight and past the 30-day cut-off date that Pacquiao had demanded for a Mayweather fight.\n\nBoth sides agreed to enter into [[mediation]] on January 7, 2010, in hopes of coming to an agreement on the blood testing issue. Retired federal judge Daniel Weinstein, who successfully resolved a prior dispute between Top Rank and Golden Boy Promotions, would again act as mediator. Two days later, after hours of negotiating during mediation, Arum declared that the fight was officially off after Mayweather refused to agree to a 24-day cut-off date. Mayweather revealed that he offered a 14-day cut-off date to Team Pacquiao, but it was rejected.\n\nMayweather Promotions CEO Leonard Ellerbe declared on January 18, 2010, that random blood and urine testing will be implemented in all of Mayweather's future fights, regardless of the opponent. On February 13, 2010, in an exclusive interview with David Mayo of The ''Grand Rapids Press'', Mayweather said, \"I gave him [Pacquiao] a chance, up to 14 days out. But my new terms are all the way up to the fight. They can come get us whenever, all the way up to the fight, random drug test. That's what it is.\"<ref name=\"timeline1\"/>\n\nAfter the failed negotiations, both fighters moved on to instead face other opponents. On March 13, 2010, Pacquiao defeated [[Joshua Clottey]] via unanimous decision, and on May 1, 2010, Mayweather beat Shane Mosley by a unanimous decision.\n\nPacquiao was quoted by the ''[[Manila Bulletin]]'' on May 20, 2010, as saying, \"As long as they're not getting a large amount of blood, I am willing to give out blood as close to two weeks before the fight.\" On the same day, Mayweather revealed that he would be taking the rest of 2010, and possibly 2011, off.\n\nOn June 10, 2010, Oscar De La Hoya said negotiations for a Mayweather-Pacquiao fight were close to being finalized. Speaking to Spanish-language sport show ''[[Rep\u00fablica Deportiva]]'', De La Hoya briefly talked about the current status of negotiations and, with a grin on his face, said that the two sides were extremely close to making the biggest fight in boxing a reality. \"These negotiations have been real difficult for various reasons, but we're really close to finalizing the contracts, even though they've been complicated,\" he commented. \"Today, I can't really talk about the negotiations, but we're really close.\" A week later, Golden Boy Promotions CEO [[Richard Schaefer]] refuted De La Hoya's comments. \"I saw those quotes as well, and I had no idea what Oscar was talking about. And I called him up and asked him about them, and he said that he was misquoted,\" Schaefer explained to Lem Satterfield of ''FanHouse''.\n\nArum declared on June 30, 2010, that there were no longer any issues and the decision was up to Mayweather. \"That's all been resolved,\" Arum stated to Kevin Iole of ''Yahoo! Sports'' regarding the dispute over random blood and urine drug testing. Arum would also tell the ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'', \"There's no longer any issues....The question is whether Mayweather is willing to fight this year.\" He would reiterate that comment to the ''Manila Bulletin'', stating, \"It's now up to Mayweather if he wants to fight.\"\n\nOn July 13, 2010, Arum issued a July 16 midnight deadline for Mayweather. \"Mayweather has until the end of the week. He could wait until the last minute. If it's Friday [July 16] and it's 11 p.m., and he says we have a deal, we have a deal,\" Arum would explain to Dan Rafael of ESPN. On July 15, 2010, Top Rank's website unveiled an official countdown to the deadline entitled \"Money\" Time: Mayweather's Decision.\n\nAs soon as the deadline for Mayweather's response expired, Arum held a conference call. Arum revealed to the media that the negotiations he had been referring to consisted of a series of conversations with HBO Sports President [[Ross Greenburg]]. He also revealed that there was no actual direct communication with any representative from Team Mayweather or Golden Boy Promotions: <blockquote>I had a couple of conversations with Ross [Greenburg] and I laid out all the terms that would be acceptable to our side and I also informed him about the concession that Manny had made regarding drug testing. He got back to me in a couple of weeks and told me that he had had discussions with [[Al Haymon]], representing Floyd Mayweather, and that everything looked good and we were nearing a resolution...The subsequent conversations with Ross detailed to me conversations he had with Al Haymon. Nowhere was the name Richard Schaefer or Golden Boy mentioned, although I read, as you all did, Oscar's statement that a deal was close, so I assumed from that Haymon was keeping Schaefer and Golden Boy abreast of the situation.</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Floyd Mayweather Jr 2011.jpg|thumb|Mayweather in 2011]]\nDuring a Q & A session following his opening statement, Arum further explained, \"We have never talked to anybody on the Mayweather side and all conversations on our part were through Ross Greenburg and he reported on all conversations on the Mayweather side from Al Haymon.\"\n\nOn July 19, 2010, Ellerbe denied that negotiations ever took place and nothing was ever agreed on. Ellerbe stated: <blockquote>Here are the facts: Al Haymon, Richard Schaefer and myself speak to each other on a regular basis and the truth is no negotiations have ever taken place nor was there ever a deal agreed upon by Team Mayweather or Floyd Mayweather to fight Manny Pacquiao on November 13. Either Ross Greenburg or Bob Arum is not telling the truth, but history tells us who is lying.</blockquote> Three days later, Schaefer backed Ellerbe's statement that negotiations never took place.\n\nWhen asked via e-mail for his response to Ellerbe's denial that negotiations ever took place, Greenburg would respond to ESPN's Dan Rafael with the following reply: \"As always we have no comment.\"\n\nRegarding comments he made suggesting that contracts for the mega-fight were close to being finalized, De La Hoya told ''BoxingScene.com'' on July 26, 2010: <blockquote>I think I said it because I get the question asked so many times that, obviously, I was fed up and tired of it and I just said like, yeah, yeah, it's gonna get made. So it was a quick answer that I should have obviously thought about. But, obviously, negotiations weren't going on. Nothing was going on.</blockquote>\n\nAlso on July 26, Greenburg released a statement saying that he had been negotiating with a representative from each side since May 2, 2010. \"I had been negotiating with a representative from each side since May 2, carefully trying to put the fight together. Hopefully, someday this fight will happen. Sports fans deserve it,\" Greenburg revealed in a prepared statement sent out to select members of the media.\n\nSchaefer again supported Ellerbe's denial of negotiations, and challenged both Greenburg and Arum to take lie detector tests. \"I think it's unfortunate that Ross made that statement. I fully stand behind the statement I made. I have not negotiated with Ross and I am not aware of any negotiations that have taken place,\" Schaefer told ESPN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fighthype.com/pages/mayweather-pacquiao-negotiations-timeline-2.html |title=Source:Mayweather-Pacquiao Negotiations Timeline Part 2 |publisher=Fighthype.com |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 8, 2011, ESPN reported that Pacquiao was willing to agree to random drug testing\u2014but not by the United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA). \"We have agreed in the Pacquiao camp to unlimited random testing done by a responsible, neutral organization,\" Arum told Yahoo. <blockquote>We don't believe USADA is a neutral organization. I don't think anybody's test is as vigorous as the test administered by the Olympic Organization. And we can arrange for the Olympic Organization to handle the test under the supervision of the Athletic commission respective of the state where the fight is going to be held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/100115.html |title=Pacquiao 'agrees to Mayweather's demands' |publisher=ESPN|date=July 8, 2011 |accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, the following day, Pacquiao's top adviser, Michael Koncz, stated that Pacquiao had never agreed to testing until fight day. \"Will we give blood five days, seven days before the fight? You know, that's something I have to talk to Manny about, but we have nothing to hide,\" Koncz said.\n\nESPN reported on January 20, 2012, that Mayweather called Pacquiao on the telephone and spoke directly with him in the Philippines. \"He ask about a 50/50 split and I told him no that can't happen, but what can happen is you can make more money fighting me then [sic] you have made in your career,\" Mayweather said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/7480500/floyd-mayweather-jr-places-telephone-call-manny-pacquiao |title=Floyd Mayweather, Manny Pacquiao talk |publisher=ESPN|date=January 20, 2012 |accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> Mayweather offered to pay him a flat fee of $40 million for a proposed fight but would not allow him to share in the revenue. Pacquiao said, \"I spoke to Floyd...and he offered me an amount,\" Pacquiao said. \"He didn't talk about the pay-per-views here and that's it. I can't agree with that. I told him I agree with 55 and 45 (split).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/8405784/manny-pacquiao-says-floyd-mayweather-jr-bigger-split-money-potential-fight |title=Manny Pacquiao waiting for fight |publisher=ESPN|date=September 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPacquiao appeared on the ESPN program ''[[First Take (TV series)|First Take]]'' on September 20, 2012, and said he had no problem with the drug-testing issue. \"No problem,\" Pacquiao said. \"Whatever he wants to do.\" Pacquiao said he was willing to be tested even on the night of the fight. \"No problem,\" he said. \"Even the night of the fight. No problem.\"\n\nOn December 20, 2013, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that Mayweather said Pacquiao's association with promoter Bob Arum is the reason why the bout will not happen. \"We all know the Pacquiao fight, at this particular time, will never happen, and the reason why the fight won't happen is because I will never do business with Bob Arum again in life, and Pacquiao is Bob Arum's fighter,\" Mayweather said.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/manny-pacquiao/10529965/Floyd-Mayweather-says-fight-with-Manny-Pacquiao-will-never-happen.html |title=Floyd Mayweather says fight with Manny Pacquiao will 'never happen' |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=December 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the ring===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Ortiz====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Victor Ortiz}}\n[[File:Floyd Mayweather, Jr. June 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Mayweather photographed at the Mayweather\u2013Ortiz press conference on June 28, 2011|alt=Mayweather smiling and flashing \"V\" for victory with his right hand]]\nOn June 7, 2011, Mayweather announced via [[Twitter]] that he was set to fight WBC welterweight champion and ''The Ring'' #2-ranked welterweight [[Victor Ortiz]] on September 17. Ortiz was Mayweather's first challenger in 16 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=6634945 |title=Floyd Mayweather to fight Victor Ortiz |publisher=ESPN  |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> The fight took place at the MGM Grand Garden Arena. From round one, Mayweather used his speed, skills and accurate right hand to tag Ortiz repeatedly. Although Mayweather seemed in control through the first three rounds, judges' scores 30\u201327, 30\u201327, and 29\u201328 for Mayweather, in the fourth round Ortiz had some success, landing a few shots and stinging Mayweather before bulling him into the corner. He then rammed Mayweather in the face with an intentional [[headbutt]], opening a [[Wound|cut]] on the inside and outside of Mayweather's mouth. Referee [[Joe Cortez]] immediately called time out and docked Ortiz a point for the blatant [[Foul (sports)|foul]]. Ortiz, apparently acknowledging his wrongdoing, hugged Mayweather in the corner and even appeared to kiss him.\n\nCortez motioned the fighters back together to resume the fight, without putting them in a neutral corner. Both fighters touched gloves, and Ortiz gave Mayweather another hug. At that moment, Cortez was not looking at the fighters. As Ortiz let go, Mayweather took advantage of Ortiz not having his hands up and unloaded a left hook which wobbled Ortiz. Ortiz then looked at the referee, and Mayweather connected with a flush right hand to Ortiz's face. Ortiz fell to the canvas, and was unable to beat Cortez's count as the crowd of 14,687 jeered Mayweather.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/6991483/floyd-mayweather-won-fight-victor-ortiz-fair-square |title=Mayweather won fair and square |publisher=ESPN |date=September 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr.'s Legal Sucker Punch|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/09/floyd-mayweather-jrs-legal-sucker-punch/245261/|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davies|first=Gareth|title=Floyd Mayweather accused of blindsiding Victor Ortiz with controversial 'sucker punch' in 4th round KO|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/sport/garethadavies/100019662/floyd-mayweather-accused-of-blindsiding-victor-ortiz-with-controversial-sucker-punch-in-4th-round-ko/|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=December 22, 2011|location=London|date=September 18, 2011}}</ref> After the fight Ortiz claimed that he was merely obeying the referee's instructions when he was \"blindsided\" by Mayweather, who defended his actions by saying that \"In the ring, you have to protect yourself at all times\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/6983926/floyd-mayweather-scores-controversial-ko-victor-ortiz |title=Mayweather scores controversial KO |publisher=ESPN  |date=September 18, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMayweather vs. Ortiz was purchased by 1.25 million homes with a value of $78,440,000 in pay-per-view revenue. These numbers make the event the second-highest-grossing non-heavyweight pay-per-view event of all time. Mayweather has appeared in the three biggest non-heavyweight pay-per-view events in the sport's history: [[Oscar De La Hoya vs. Floyd Mayweather|Mayweather vs. Oscar De La Hoya]] ($136,853,700), Mayweather vs. Ortiz ($78,440,000), and [[Floyd Mayweather vs. Shane Mosley|Mayweather vs. Shane Mosley]] ($78,330,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fighthype.com/pages/content11072.html |title=Fighthype \\\\ The Numbers Are In! Mayweather-Ortiz Is Second Highest Grossing Non-Heavyweight Fight |publisher=Fighthype.com |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Return to light middleweight===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Cotto====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Miguel Cotto}}\nMayweather's adviser, Leonard Ellerbe, announced on November 2, 2011, that Mayweather would return to the ring on May 5, 2012, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas. After negotiations with Manny Pacquiao failed again, on February 1, 2012, it was confirmed that Mayweather would be moving up in weight to fight WBA super welterweight champion and ''The Ring'' #1-ranked light middleweight Miguel Cotto. The WBC put their [[super welterweight]] diamond belt at stake.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.doghouseboxing.com/John/Raspanti041712.htm |title=Diamond belt at stake for Mayweather and Cotto |publisher=www.doghouseboxing.com |accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of Saturday, May 5, Mayweather defeated Cotto in 12 rounds by a unanimous decision, improving his record to 43\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|title=Floyd Mayweather wins unanimous decision over Miguel Cotto|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-mayweather-cotto-round-by-round-updates-20120505,0,7518951.story?track=rss/|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=May 6, 2012|location=Las Vegas|date=May 5, 2012}}</ref> Mayweather used movement and outboxed Cotto in the middle of the ring for the first few rounds. Beginning in rounds three and four Cotto cut the ring off from Mayweather, forcing the latter to fight from the ropes. However, Mayweather seemed to outfight Cotto from the ropes with his combinations and by rolling with most of Cotto's punches. Cotto had more success in the middle rounds, landing his jab and body shots on Mayweather and effectively trapping him on the ropes. The later rounds were controlled by Mayweather, who boxed more in the center of the ring late in the fight. In the 12th round Mayweather's uppercut stunned and hurt Cotto, but Cotto was able to fight until the end. The judges scored the fight a unanimous decision for Mayweather by scores of 118\u2013110, 117\u2013111, and 117\u2013111. After the fight, Mayweather said Cotto was the toughest fighter he ever faced.\n\nCompuBox had Mayweather outlanding and outworking Cotto in the fight by a significant margin. Mayweather landed 26 percent of his total punches (179 out of 687), compared with 21 percent (105 out of 506) for Cotto. In power punches, Mayweather landed 128 of 382 (34 percent), compared with 75 of 329 (23 percent) for Cotto.<ref>{{cite web|author=Slagter, Josh |url=http://www.mlive.com/mayweather/index.ssf/2012/05/floyd_mayweather_not_as_domina.html |title=Floyd Mayweather not as dominant as usual in CompuBox stats in win over Miguel Cotto |publisher=MLive.com |date= |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Mayweather earned the biggest guaranteed purse in boxing history ($32&nbsp;million) when he fought Cotto, according to contracts filed with the Nevada State Athletic Commission.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rafael, Dan |url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/7891335/floyd-mayweather-jr-make-history-32-million-take |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. to make history with $32 million take \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=May 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The Mayweather-Cotto fight generated $94&nbsp;million in PPV revenue from 1.5&nbsp;million purchases, making it the second-biggest non-heavyweight fight in history (after Mayweather's fight with Oscar De La Hoya).<ref>{{cite web|author=Rafael, Dan |url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/7919965/floyd-mayweather-miguel-cotto-rakes-94m-ppv-sales |title=Floyd Mayweather-Miguel Cotto rakes in $94M in PPV sales \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=May 11, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Jail term and repercussions===\nOn June 1, 2012, Mayweather reported to the [[Clark County Detention Center]] in Las Vegas to serve his jail term for [[domestic abuse]]. After serving two months, he was released from prison on August 3, 2012.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2012/06/01/sport/boxer-mayweather-jailed/index.html CNN]</ref><ref>[https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/8228834/floyd-mayweather-jr-released-vegas-jail-serving-2-months ESPN]</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2015, Mayweather, who was planning to do a tour in Australia, was [[Visa policy of Australia|denied]] a [[visa (document)|visa]] on the basis of his criminal record and jail term.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/boxing/floyd-mayweather-denied-visa-over-family-violence-convictions-20150204-135mkz.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Floyd Mayweather denied visa over family violence convictions}}</ref>\n\n===Mandatory title defense at welterweight===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Guerrero====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Robert Guerrero}}\nMayweather returned to the ring on May 4, 2013, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena to face the WBC interim welterweight champion, ''Ring'' No. 3 ranked welterweight, and the WBC's mandatory challenger [[Robert Guerrero]]. This was Mayweather's first fight since being released from jail, and was the first time Mayweather has fought on Showtime PPV after a long relationship with HBO. Mayweather was guaranteed $32 million for the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/9240531/floyd-mayweather-jr-earn-record-tying-guarantee-32-million-fight-robert-guerrero |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. ties purse mark |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=May 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe fight took place in front of 15,880 at the MGM Grand Garden Arena. Prior to the fight, Guerrero had not lost in 8 years. The first couple rounds were fairly even, with Mayweather attempting to counter and time Guerrero, while Guerrero was attempting to drive Mayweather to the ropes and make it a rough fight. After the first couple rounds, Mayweather was in complete control, almost hitting Guerrero at will with right hand leads, counters, hooks, and effectively timing Guerrero the rest of the fight. Mayweather won the fight on all three scorecards 117\u2013111. Mayweather outlanded Guerrero 195 punches to 113, which included a rare 60% connect on his power shots.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/9243631/floyd-money-mayweather-dominates-robert-guerrero-12-round-decision-welterweight-title|title=Mayweather masterful, dominates Guerrero|work=ESPN.com|access-date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough no official tallies are reported, according to Showtime Sports executive [[Stephen Espinoza]], the fight had exceeded 1 million purchases in PPV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2013/05/mayweather-vs-guerrero-exceeds-1-million-ppv-buys/ |title=Mayweather vs. Guerrero exceeds 1 million PPV buys |publisher=Boxingnews24.com |date=May 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Third return to light middleweight===\n====Mayweather vs. \u00c1lvarez====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Sa\u00fal \u00c1lvarez}}\nMayweather confirmed via Twitter that a deal was reached to face ''Ring'' No. 10 ranked pound for pound, WBC and WBA Super welterweight champion [[Sa\u00fal \u00c1lvarez|Sa\u00fal \"Canelo\" \u00c1lvarez]] in a championship bout on September 14, 2013, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/mayweather-says-canelo-fight-done-sept-14--66050 |title=Mayweather Says Canelo Fight is Done For Sept. 14 |publisher=Boxing News |website=Boxingscene.com |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> A catchweight of 152 pounds was established for the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/9323856/floyd-mayweather-jr-fight-canelo-alvarez-sept-14 |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. to fight Canelo Alvarez on Sept. 14 |website=Espn.go.com |date=June 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> Mayweather received a boxing record $41.5 million for the Alvarez fight, according to Leonard Ellerbe, Mayweather's confidant.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2013/09/04/floyd-mayweather-to-get-record-41-5-million-guarantee-for-canelo-alvarez-fight/ Floyd Mayweather To Get Record $41.5 Million Guarantee For Canelo Alvarez Fight]. Forbes (April 9, 2013). Retrieved on September 5, 2013.</ref> In front of a sold out crowd of 16,746 at the MGM Garden, Mayweather defeated \u00c1lvarez by majority twelve-round decision. In a fight that many thought was going to be Mayweather's toughest, he outclassed the younger \u00c1lvarez. Many observers at ringside thought Mayweather won all twelve rounds. Judge [[C. J. Ross]] scored the fight 114\u2013114, a draw. Judge Dave Moretti had it 116\u2013112, and Craig Metcalfe scored it 117\u2013111. Judge Ross retired after this fight. Speaking of the controversial scorecard, Mayweather said, \"I can't control what the judges do.\" Compubox stats showed Mayweather's dominance in the fight, landed 232 of 505 punches (46%) and 117 connected of 526 thrown (22%) for \u00c1lvarez, who earned a base purse of $5 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/9676698/floyd-mayweather-jr-earns-easy-decision-canelo-alvarez|title=Mayweather gets easy decision over Alvarez|work=ESPN.com|access-date=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/15/sports/with-easy-victory-mayweather-ensures-hype-is-just-that.html|title=With Easy Victory, Mayweather Ensures Hype Is Just That|last=Eligon|first=John|date=September 15, 2013|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/23992694|title=As it happened|date=September 15, 2013|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=September 17, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917061601/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/23992694|archive-date=September 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/18/cj-ross-mayweather-alvarez-judge-boxing_n_3949804.html|title=Judge CJ Ross retires|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920231029/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/18/cj-ross-mayweather-alvarez-judge-boxing_n_3949804.html|archive-date=September 20, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Welterweight unification===\n====Mayweather vs. Maidana I====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Marcos Maidana}}\nDespite interest in a bout with [[Amir Khan (boxer)|Amir Khan]], Mayweather announced that he would fight 30 year old [[Marcos Maidana]] (35\u20133, 31 KOs) on May 3, 2014, in a unification bout at MGM Grand Garden Arena, with Mayweather's WBC and ''The Ring'' welterweight titles at stake, as well as Maidana's WBA (Super) welterweight title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/320735-push-live-when-announcement-is-made-floyd-mayweather-jr-picks-marcos-maidana-over-amir-khan|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. picks Marcos Maidana over Amir Khan|work=Ring TV|accessdate=February 24, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301210438/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/320735-push-live-when-announcement-is-made-floyd-mayweather-jr-picks-marcos-maidana-over-amir-khan|archivedate=March 1, 2014}}</ref> Maidana won the WBA tite in [[Adrien Broner vs. Marcos Maidana|December 2013]] against Mayweather friend, [[Adrien Broner]]. Mayweather tweeted the news the day after his 37th birthday. The [[Barclays Center]] in Brooklyn also made a case to showcase the fight. Mayweather explained why he chose Maidana, \"Marcos Maidana's last performance immediately brought him to my attention. He is an extremely skilled fighter who brings knockout danger to the ring. I think this is a great fight for me and he deserves the opportunity to see if he can do what 45 others have tried to do before him \u2013 beat me.\" Maidana was a 12-to-1 underdog going into the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10513894/floyd-mayweather-jr-lines-marcos-maidana-next-fight|title=Mayweather lines up Maidana for next fight|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn front of a sold-out crowd of 16,268, in what was one of his toughest fights, Mayweather won the bout via majority decision, with scores of 114\u2013114, 117\u2013111, and 116\u2013112. Maidana came out aggressive and maintained that stance throughout the fight forcing Mayweather to engage. CompuBox revealed that Mayweather was hit more times than any of his previous 38 bouts that have been covered by them. Mayweather landed 230 of his 426 punches thrown (54%) while Maidana landed 221 of 858 (26%). Many times in the fight Maidana threw shots at different angles, forcing Mayweather against the ropes. According to Mayweather in the post fight interview, Maidana's aggressive approach made him change his style of fighting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2014/05/04/floyd-mayweather-maidana-majority-decision-las-vegas/8667891/|title=Floyd Mayweather beats Marcos Maidana, but crowd unhappy|work=USA TODAY|access-date=August 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMaidana was guaranteed a purse of $1.5 million, which would also include TV revenue from his native Argentina and PPV share. Mayweather earned a minimum $32 million. There were calls for an immediate rematch. Mayweather said, \"He put pressure on me and that's when I decided to fight differently,\" Mayweather said. \"I stood there and fought him. He's a good fighter, I take nothing away from him [...] This was a tough, competitive fight. This is what fans want to see. \"I want to give fans an exciting fight. Normally, I box and move. Tonight, I gave fans an exciting fight.\" Maidana felt he won the fight, believing he gave Mayweather his toughest fight ever. Speaking through a translator, he said, \"I definitely think I won. Floyd had never been hit by a man before. I had to change the gloves [after a last-minute problem with his original gloves on Friday] and I still gave him a great fight. He did dominate some rounds but the majority, I dominated them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10879956/floyd-mayweather-jr-scores-majority-decision-marcos-maidana-welterweight-unification-fight|title=Mayweather decisions Maidana in thriller|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe generated around 900,000 although exact figures were not released by Showtime. The revenue of PPV sale amounted to $58 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/boxing/counter-punch/2014/05/29/floyd-mayweather-marcos-maidana-boxing|title=Mayweather-Maidana fight generates less than 1 million pay per view buys|work=SI.com|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Maidana II====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Marcos Maidana II}}\nOn July 10, 2014, Mayweather made the announcement that a rematch with Maidana (35\u20134, 31 KOs) was confirmed. The fight was to take place on September 13, 2014, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena, with Mayweather's WBA (Super), WBC and ''The Ring'' welterweight titles at stake, as well as Mayweather's WBC light middleweight title. The fight was billed as he fight billed as \"Mayhem\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2014/07/10/floyd-mayweather-announces-rematch-versus-marcos-maidana/+&cd=7&c|title=Floyd Mayweather Announces Rematch Versus Marcos Maidana|last=Badenhausen|first=Kurt|work=Forbes|access-date=August 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9378594/floyd-mayweather-confirms-marcos-maidana-rematch-on-september-13|title= Floyd Mayweather confirms Marcos Maidana rematch on September 13|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/news/2014/07/30/mayweather-and-maidana-to-fight-for-two-weight-wbc-titles.html |title=Mayweather and Maidana to fight for two-weight WBC titles |work=World Boxing News |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802034800/http://www.worldboxingnews.net/news/2014/07/30/mayweather-and-maidana-to-fight-for-two-weight-wbc-titles.html |archivedate=August 2, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn front of 16,144 at the MGM Grand, Mayweather defeated Maidana via unanimous decision. Unlike the first fight, Mayweather came out better prepared for Maidana's style. The final judges scores were 115\u2013112, 116\u2013111, and 116\u2013111. ESPN scored it wider for Mayweather at 119\u2013108. Mayweather did not allow Maidana to land any overhand right, with the punch stats showing Maidana connecting 128 of 572 shots (22%). Mayweather had 51% connect rate landing 166 of 326.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chen, Brian |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2197732-mayweather-vs-maidana-2-live-round-by-round-results-and-highlights |title=Mayweather vs. Maidana 2: Live Round-by-Round Results and Highlights |publisher=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=September 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA bizarre moment occurred in round 8, whilst in a headlock, Maidana appeared to have bitten Mayweather's left hand. Mayweather explained this in the post fight, \"I didn't know what it was. Something happened and then my fingers were numb. After the eighth round my fingers were numb. I could only use my other hand. He bit me. I realized he bit me. We were tangled in the middle of the ring and all of a sudden I felt something on my left hand.\" Maidana denied the bite, \"Maybe he thinks I'm a dog, but I never bit him. He was rubbing my eyes that round. He may have had his glove in my mouth, but I never bit him.\" After round 9, Maidana appeared to be confused as he started walking towards the wrong corner. Mayweather immediately ran towards him to point to his corner, much to the amusement of the crowd. Maidana was unhappy with the final verdict and thought he won the fight, \"If the judges want to give the fight to fighters that run, they can give it to him. I was attacking all the time. Maybe I'm wrong, but I thought that I was the aggressor. I kept my plan to be aggressive but he kept holding and pushing. I don't want to waste my time with a third fight. I trained with all my heart to get this type of result. This is not fair. There's not reason for another fight.\" For the sequel, Mayweather earned a minimum of $32 million and Maidana earned a career high $3 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/11522417/floyd-mayweather-jr-scores-unanimous-decision-marcos-maidana-rematch|title=Mayweather decisions Maidana in rematch|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/9/14/6146209/mayweather-vs-maidana-results-floyd-mayweather-wins-easier-decision|title=Mayweather wins easier in rematch with Maidana|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014/9/14/6146479/mayweather-vs-maidana-2-results-floyd-mayweather-wins-rematch-by|title=Mayweather takes decision win over Maidana|last=Brookhouse|first=Brent|date=September 14, 2014|website=SBNation.com|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe fight did well on PPV, a reported 925,000 households bought the fight, generating $60 million. The live gate grossed nearly $15 million, putting it at number 5 in the top 35 boxing gates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/9/19/6526031/mayweather-maidana-ii-does-good-numbers-on-ppv-and-live-gate+&|title=Mayweather-Maidana II performs well on PPV|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Mayweather vs. Pacquiao====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather vs. Manny Pacquiao}}\n[[File:Floyd Mayweather jr weigh-in.jpg|thumb|right|Mayweather during the official weigh-in, 2015]]\nMayweather fought [[Manny Pacquiao]], after negotiations spread over a number of years, on May 2, 2015, inside [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rafael|first1=Dan|title=Mayweather-Pacquiao set for May 2|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/12355361/floyd-mayweather-announces-fight-manny-pacquiao-set-2|accessdate=February 21, 2015|publisher=ESPN.com|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref> Mayweather dictated the pace early, controlling range with the jab. His deft movement and pivoting made Pacquiao, who landed only 19% of his punches, consistently miss. Mayweather was able to counter Pacquiao with his right hand constantly throughout the fight and won via unanimous decision with the scorecards reading 118\u2013110, 116\u2013112, and 116\u2013112.<ref>{{cite web|title=Floyd Mayweather beats Manny Pacquiao in unanimous decision|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/12810858/floyd-mayweather-defeats-manny-pacquiao-unanimous-decision|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> The vast majority of media outlets (16/18) scored the bout in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmadecisions.com/decision/6144/Floyd-Mayweather-vs-Manny-Pacquiao|title=Floyd Mayweather def. Manny Pacquiao|publisher=mmadecisions.com |date= May 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/32571743|title=Floyd Mayweather beats Manny Pacquiao in Las Vegas|date=May 3, 2015|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> In the days following the fight, many observers felt the match failed to live up to expectations. Pacquiao told the media after the match that he was limited in the fight due to an injured right arm. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported that Pacquiao fought through a torn rotator cuff in his right shoulder, which will require surgery.<ref>{{cite web|title = Dr. Surena Namdari on Manny Pacquiao's injury, surgery and rehab|url = https://www.si.com/boxing/2015/05/05/manny-pacquiao-shoulder-injury-surgery-doctor-explanation|accessdate = May 6, 2015}}</ref> [[Bob Arum]] revealed Pacquiao's injury to have been a persistent one dating back to 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/05/bob-arum-says-manny-pacquiaos-shoulder-has-been-injured-since-2008 | work=USA Today | title=Bob Arum says Manny Pacquiao's shoulder has been injured since 2008}}</ref> Additionally Pacquiao's camp had not requested a cortisone injection, which is allowed by the [[US Anti-Doping Agency]], but rather a last-minute toradol injection, which was declined by the [[Nevada State Athletic Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5L6OH_LMnPM |title=paulie malignaggi goes off on manny pacquiao shot request before floyd fight \u2013 EsNews |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=June 20, 2015 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> Mayweather, who originally had no plans for a rematch with Pacquiao, told ESPN's [[Stephen A. Smith]] in a text that he would be open to a rematch after Pacquiao recovers from shoulder surgery, however {{as of|2015|May|9|lc=y|df=US}}, Mayweather stated \"Did I text Stephen A. Smith and say I will fight him again? Yeah, but I change my mind. At this particular time, no, because he's a sore loser and he's a coward.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Floyd Mayweather declares no rematch for 'sore loser' Manny Pacquiao|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/12843122/floyd-mayweather-changes-mind-says-not-grant-manny-pacquiao-rematch|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=May 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Floyd Mayweather says he'd be willing to fight Manny Pacquiao again|url = http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/12824362/floyd-mayweather-says-willing-fight-manny-pacquiao-again|accessdate = May 6, 2015}}</ref>   On July 6, 2015, the [[World Boxing Organization]] (WBO) stripped Mayweather of his welterweight championship on technical grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2516276-floyd-mayweather-officially-stripped-of-wbo-147-pound-welterweight-title|title=Floyd Mayweather Officially Stripped of WBO 147-Pound Welterweight Title|publisher=Bleacher Report|date=July 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Second retirement===\n\n====Mayweather vs. Berto====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Andre Berto}}\nMayweather confirmed through Instagram that he would defend the WBC, WBA (Super), and The Ring welterweight titles against WBA interim champion [[Andre Berto]] on September 12, 2015, at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]]. The announcement received some backlash due to Berto being (3\u20133) in his last 6 fights. Many felt he wasn't a credible opponent. Welterweight contender Amir Khan was said to be disappointed with the selection.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9935653/amir-khan-disappointed-to-miss-out-on-floyd-mayweather-fight|title=Amir Khan 'disappointed' Floyd Mayweather chose Berto|work=Sky Sports|access-date=August 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Berto believed Mayweather chose him as his final opponent due to personal reasons, which could date back to when he won the [[Golden Gloves|National Golden Gloves]] tournament.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2015/9/10/9300713/berto-believes-mayweather-chose-him-because-of-personal-issue+&cd=3&ct=clnk&gl=uk|title=Berto: Floyd chose me because of personal beef|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref> Showtimes, [[Stephen Espinoza]] revealed the reason why Mayweather never chose Amir Khan, was because Khan would have been observing [[Ramadan]] before the fight and therefore wouldn't be \"at the top of his game\". The reason to why he decided not to fight then IBF titleholder [[Kell Brook]] was a business decision, with Brook not being known in the US compared to Berto.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/34206788|title=Floyd Mayweather: Amir Khan and Kell Brook not suitable opponents|date=September 10, 2015|work=BBC Sport|access-date=August 29, 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/floyd-mayweather-jr-confirms-fight-against-andre-berto-359866|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. Confirms Fight Against Andre Berto|date=August 4, 2015|newspaper=Newsweek|access-date=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ringtv.com/396197-floyd-mayweather-jr-vs-andre-berto-its-official/|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Andre Berto: It's official \u2013 The Ring|date=August 4, 2015|work=The Ring|access-date=August 29, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMayweather was able to pinpoint holes in Berto's guard and find a home for the jab early. He landed sharp counters and feint hooks while controlling range for the vast majority of the bout. Berto pushed the pace, but his aggressiveness fell short as Mayweather was highly mobile and closed the distance consistently.<ref name=\"fighthype.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fighthype.com/news/article21874.html |title=[Video&#93; Keith Thurman Reacts To Mayweather'S Final Fight Victory: \"Beautiful...Better Than Pacquiao Night\" |website=Fighthype.Com |date=September 13, 2015 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> Mayweather hurt his left hand at the end of the ninth round but remained comfortable throughout the rest of the fight, winning via unanimous decision 117\u2013111, 118\u2013110, and 120\u2013108. Mayweather dominated the fight, landing an impressive 56% [232/410] punches thrown, compared to Berto's underwhelming number of 17% [83/495] punches landed. Mayweather earned a purse of $32 million and Berto earned a career-high $4 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/13644159/floyd-mayweather-earns-unanimous-decision-win-andre-berto-likely-final-fight|title=Mayweather dominates Berto, caps 49\u20130 career|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Christ |first=Scott |url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2015/9/12/9314693/mayweather-vs-berto-live-streaming-results-and-round-by-round-coverage |title=Mayweather vs Berto: Live streaming results and round by round coverage |publisher=Bad Left Hook |date=September 12, 2015 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nEarly industry sources reported the fight drew 550,000 buys.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-boxing-mayweather-berto-showtime-pay-per-view-worst-20150916-story.html|title=Floyd Mayweather's worst Showtime pay-per-view haul, in perspective|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|date=September 16, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=August 28, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Later sources indicated the number could have been as low as 400,000 buys, generating $28 million. This was the lowest number of buys Floyd had generated in over 10 years. The fight also gathered a crowd of 13,395, also a decreased figure compared to Mayweather previous fights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13681951/floyd-mayweather-andre-berto-fight-disappoints-pay-per-view-sales|title=Source: Mayweather-Berto PPV as low as 400K|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Keith Thurman]] noted, \"Amazing speed ... he showed tremendous skill and talent.\"<ref name=\"fighthype.com\" /> Mayweather announced his retirement in the ring after defeating Berto, walking away from the sport with an undefeated record of 49\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/sep/13/floyd-mayweather-finishes-up-unbeaten-after-one-sided-victory-over-andre-berto|title=Floyd Mayweather 'ends career' undefeated after one-sided victory over Andre Berto|last=Graham|first=Bryan Armen|date=September 13, 2015|work=|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=December 23, 2016|via=}}</ref> The WBC declared his welterweight and super welterweight titles vacant in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Bob|title=WBC 53rd convention report: Day 3 \u2013 Mandatory Defenses and More|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/wbc-53rd-convention-report-day-2-mandatory-defenses-and-more-312213#more-312213|website=Fightnews.com|accessdate=November 10, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108024432/http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/wbc-53rd-convention-report-day-2-mandatory-defenses-and-more-312213#more-312213|archivedate=November 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Return and Third retirement===\n\n====Mayweather vs. McGregor====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Conor McGregor}}\nThe idea of a Mayweather comeback floated around April 2016, as rumors of Mayweather Promotions filing for trademarks of \"TBE 50\" and \"TMT 50\" hinted that Mayweather might have been targeting that 50th win. This was confirmed by posts from the U.S. Patent and Trademark website.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/15441735/floyd-mayweather-company-files-50-trademarks|title=Mayweather's company files for '50' trademarks|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAround May 2016, another rumor started that a crossover fight between Mayweather and MMA star [[Conor McGregor]] was in the works. On May 7, 2016, Mayweather confirmed that he was the one who started the rumors regarding the potential clash.<ref>{{cite web|author=MMA Hot Sauce |url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/floyd-mayweather-confirms-conor-mcgregor-rumors-that-he-started |title=Floyd Mayweather Confirms Conor McGregor Rumors... That He Started! |website=MMAWeekly.com |date=May 8, 2016 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> Mayweather followed it through with an Instagram post of an unofficial teaser poster showcasing both fighters. [[Dana White]] dismissed all the rumors and stated that Mayweather had yet to contact him in case he wanted the fight to push through, since McGregor was in contract with the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Guillen |first=Adam |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2016/5/12/11658864/ufc-dana-white-floyd-mayweather-if-you-want-conor-mcgregor-fight-call-me-mma |title=Dana White to Floyd Mayweather: If you want to fight Conor McGregor, call me! |website=MMAmania.com |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> On January 13, 2017, White continued his stance against a Mayweather-McGregor boxing matchup and insisted it would never happen due to McGregor's contract and even went as far as offering Mayweather to box McGregor in the UFC for $25 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/1/13/14268580/ufc-mma-boxing-super-fight-news-dana-white-floyd-mayweather-conor-mcgregor|title=White offers Mayweather $25 million to fight McGregor in boxing|last=Mckeever|first=Lewis|date=January 13, 2017|website=Bloody Elbow|access-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2017, Mayweather urged McGregor to sign the contract, hinting that a fight was really in the works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/3/7/14844420/floyd-mayweathers-message-to-conor-mcgregor-sign-the-paper|title=Floyd Mayweather\u2019s message to Conor McGregor: \u2018Sign the paper\u2019|last=Doyle|first=Dave|date=March 7, 2017|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> On March 10, 2017, Mayweather stated that only a fight with McGregor would make him come out of retirement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/3/11/14892400/floyd-mayweather-im-officially-out-of-retirement-for-conor-mcgregor|title=Floyd Mayweather: \u2018I\u2019m officially out of retirement for Conor McGregor\u2019|last=Newswire|first=MMA Fighting|date=March 11, 2017|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> On March 16, 2017, Dana White backpedaled on his stance against Mayweather fighting McGregor and said that he would not deprive McGregor of making a massive payday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/boxing/780013/Conor-McGregor-v-Floyd-Mayweather-UFC-president-Dana-White-allows-go-ahead|title=Conor McGregor v Floyd Mayweather: UFC president makes U-turn on fight|last=Gray|first=James|date=March 16, 2017|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=June 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uproxx.com/sports/conan-obrien-conor-mcgregor-floyd-mayweather-fight-update-dana-white/|title=Dana White Gives Conan A Positive Update On McGregor Vs. Mayweather|date=March 16, 2017|work=UPROXX|access-date=June 15, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> On May 18, 2017, McGregor reportedly agreed to all of Mayweather's updated terms and signed the contract.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/news/conor-mcgregor-signs-contract-to-fight-floyd-mayweather-w482909|title=Conor McGregor Signs 'Record-Breaking Deal' to Fight Floyd Mayweather|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2017, after months of negotiations, both fighters announced via their Twitter accounts that they would fight on August 26, 2017, at the [[T-Mobile Arena]] in Las Vegas, Nevada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/floyd-mayweather-conor-mcgregor-fight-finalized-aug-26-205101486.html|title=Floyd Mayweather-Conor McGregor fight finalized for Aug. 26|access-date=June 14, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> On August 24, 2017, it was announced that Mayweather and McGregor would be facing off for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Money Belt, specifically made for the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2017/08/24/mayweather-mcgregor-fight-new-wbc-money-belt-encrusted-3600/|title=Mayweather and McGregor to fight for the new WBC \"Money Belt\"}}</ref> According to the [[Nevada Athletic Commission|Nevada State Athletic Commission]], Mayweather would earn a guaranteed purse of $100 million and McGregor was guaranteed $30 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/mayweather-mcgregor-huge-guarantees-ppv-clash--119839|title=Mayweather, McGregor Have Huge Guarantees For PPV Clash \u2013 Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn front of 14,623, far short of a sell-out, Mayweather won via TKO in the 10th round, surpassing [[Rocky Marciano]] and setting the record for the longest active unbeaten streak in a professional career at 50\u20130. In the opening round, Mayweather, as per previous fights, started slow to work out McGregor's tactics. In his post-fight interview, he revealed it was part of the game plan to let McGregor punch himself out in the early rounds. McGregor won the first round on all three judges scorecards, the same case could have been made for the opening three rounds. McGregor was warned a few times through the fight for hitting behind the head, but no points were deducted by referee Robert Byrd. By the fourth round, McGregor began to tire and breathe heavily with his mouth open. Mayweather started to take control and landed with his right hands. For the next few rounds, McGregor came out throwing shots in the opening 30 seconds, but immediately tired, giving Mayweather enough time to carry on landing clean shots and winning the rounds. By round 9, McGregor had almost nothing left. Although he didn't look hurt, he was very fatigued and his face started showing redness. Two of the judges scored the round 10\u20138 for Mayweather. In round 10, McGregor staggered across the ring and was in a bad way against the ropes as Mayweather landed some hard shots. With McGregor barely on his feet after a few unanswered punches, the referee waved the fight off. The time of stoppage was 1 minute and 5 seconds of round 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/floyd-mayweather-stops-conor-mcgregor-10th-round--119882|title=Floyd Mayweather Stops Conor McGregor in 10th Round \u2013 Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of stoppage, the scorecards read 87\u201383, 89\u201382, and 89\u201381 for Mayweather. McGregor was praised by Dana White at the post-fight press conference for landing 111 punches of 430 thrown (26%) on Mayweather, more than what Pacquiao or any of Mayweather's previous nine opponents had landed. Mayweather was more than twice as accurate, however, landing 170 of 320 punches thrown (53%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20471276/floyd-mayweather-defeats-conor-mcgregor-tko-10th-round|title=Mayweather stops fading McGregor in Round 10|work=ESPN.com|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMayweather said of the fight, \"This was my last fight. Tonight, ladies and gentlemen, for sure I chose the right dance partner to dance with. Conor McGregor, you are a hell of a champion.\" He added, \"He\u2019s a tough competitor and I think we gave the fans what they wanted to see. I owed them for the Pacquiao fight. I must come straight ahead and give the fans a show, and that\u2019s what I gave them.\" McGregor felt the fight was stopped prematurely, but nevertheless respected the decision and admitted he was tired.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Emons|first1=Michael|title=Mayweather beats McGregor with 10th-round stoppage \u2013 reaction|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/boxing/40874881|website=BBC.com|publisher=BBC|accessdate=August 27, 2017}}</ref> Mayweather agreed with the stoppage, and explained that he avoided inflicting more damage on McGregor to protect him from brain damage, saying \"He has a career. You know, he still has a career. ...(It could've been) very damaging.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Corner|first1=Blue|title=Floyd Mayweather says he didn't knock out Conor McGregor to protect him from brain damage|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/09/floyd-mayweather-conor-mcgregor-brain-damage|website=mmajunkie.com|accessdate=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNevada State Athletic Commission announced the live gate for the event was $55,414,865.79 from 13,094 tickets sold and 137 complimentary tickets given out. This was far less than the [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao|Mayweather vs. Pacquiao]] fight which grossed $72 million from a paid attendance of 16,219 in 2015, despite claims from Ellerbe and Mayweather that it did more than $80 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/floyd-mayweather-vs-conor-mcgregor-live-gate-falls-well-short-of-all-time-record|title=Floyd Mayweather vs. Conor McGregor Live Gate Falls Well Short of All-Time Record {{!}} MMAWeekly.com|website=www.mmaweekly.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 6, 2017}}</ref> [[Sky Sports]] announced the fight garnered over a million PPV buys in the UK and grossed in excess of \u00a320 million, surpassing the record set in April 2017 when [[Anthony Joshua vs. Wladimir Klitschko|Anthony Joshua defeated Wladimir Klitschko]] in front of 90,000 at the [[Wembley Stadium]]. This also meant the fight generated more buys in the UK than [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao|Mayweather-Pacquiao]] which took place in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnewsonline.net/sky-sports-confirm-mayweather-mcgregor-breaks-uk-record-for-ppv-buys/|title=Sky Sports confirm Mayweather-McGregor breaks UK record for PPV buys - Boxing News|date=September 7, 2017|work=Boxing News|access-date=September 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMayweather reportedly earned over $300 million from the fight, while McGregor is expected to earn around $100 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Peter|first1=John|title=Conor McGregor has auditors 'like (expletive) sharks' for Floyd Mayweather fight purse|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2017/08/27/conor-mcgregor-has-auditors-like-expletive-sharks-floyd-mayweather-fight-purse/606286001/|website=usatoday.com|accessdate=September 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aol.com/article/news/2017/08/27/youll-never-guess-how-much-money-floyd-maywhether-made-in-his/23187328/|title=You'll never guess how much money Floyd Mayweather made in his fight against Conor McGregor|last=Staff|first=AOL|work=AOL.com|access-date=August 30, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/boxing-fifty-mayweather-stops-brave-mcgregor-053959523--box.html Fifty and out as Mayweather stops brave McGregor], August 27, 2017, Yahoo.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2017/08/27/mayweather-vs-mcgregor-prize-money-much-floyd-mayweather-take/ What is the Mayweather vs McGregor prize money and how much did Floyd Mayweather Jnr. take home?], ''The Telegraph'', August 30, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Exhibition===\n\n==== Mayweather vs. Nasukawa ====\nIn September 2018, during the electronic music festival [[Ultra Japan]], both Mayweather and Pacquiao posted videos of encounters at the festival, which implicated the possibility of a rematch. It is unknown if any formal negotiations actually occurred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/24682880/floyd-mayweather-says-rematch-manny-pacquiao-coming-year|title=Mayweather: Pacquiao rematch coming this year|work=ESPN.com|access-date=September 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/other-sport/boxing/manny-pacquiao-responds-floyd-mayweather-13250966|title=Manny Pacquiao responds to Floyd Mayweather claim superstars are set for rematch|last=Rathborn|first=Jack|date=September 15, 2018|work=irishmirror|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-sp-boxing-newsletter-20180918-story.html|title=The Fight Corner: Smooth sailing toward a Floyd Mayweather Jr.-Manny Pacquiao rematch|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|website=latimes.com|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/boxing/news/promotional-king-floyd-mayweather-steals-the-canelo-vs-ggg-2-spotlight-from-across-the-globe/|title=Promotional king Floyd Mayweather steals the Canelo vs. GGG 2 spotlight from across the globe|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=September 19, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2018/9/15/17863728/floyd-mayweather-coming-out-of-retirement-rematch-manny-pacquiao-boxing-news|title=Floyd Mayweather claims he\u2019s coming out of retirement to rematch Manny Pacquiao in December|work=Bloody Elbow|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2018, Mayweather stated in an interview that, despite references to \"this year\" in the videos, he planned to hold a fight in Japan before any possible rematch with Pacquiao.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/24735887/floyd-mayweather-planning-tuneup-fight-japan-manny-pacquiao-rematch|title=Mayweather plans tuneup before Pacquiao bout|work=ESPN.com|access-date=October 11, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On October 18, 2018, Pacquiao told the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' that a rumoured rematch with Mayweather would occur in 2019, as Mayweather was planning to fight an unnamed opponent on December 31, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Domin |first1=Martin |title=Floyd Mayweather's return date revealed by Manny Pacquiao |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/boxing/floyd-mayweather-fight-new-years-13436494 |website=Daily Mirror |accessdate=November 5, 2018 |date=October 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nesn.com/2018/10/manny-pacquiao-claims-floyd-mayweathers-next-fight-to-happen-on-this-date/|title=Manny Pacquiao Claims Floyd Mayweather\u2019s Next Fight Will Happen On This Date|date=October 18, 2018|work=NESN.com|access-date=November 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> On November 5, 2018, the Japanese MMA promotion [[Rizin Fighting Federation]] announced that Mayweather would face undefeated kickboxer [[Tenshin Nasukawa]] at [[2018 in Rizin Fighting Federation#Rizin 14 - Saitama|Rizin 14]] on December 31, 2018, under unspecified rules. Of the bout, Mayweather stated in a press conference that \"it wasn't easy to make this happen, but we told the people anything is possible, so now we're here and we wanna make sure that we give the people in [[Tokyo]] what they wanna see \u2014 blood, sweat and tears.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2018/11/4/18063380/floyd-mayweather-jr-tenshin-nasukawa-fight-boxing-kickboxer-undefeated-japan|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. to face undefeated kickboxer Tenshin Nasukawa on New Year\u2019s Eve|work=SBNation.com|access-date=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, two days later, Mayweather denied that he would actually be fighting Nasukawa. He explained that he had been booked for a non-televised exhibition for \"a small group of wealthy spectators\" during the event, but that he was caught off-guard by the announcement that he would face Nasukawa\u2014claiming that he was unaware of the fighter until the press conference, and stating that \"for the sake of the several fans and attendees that flew in from all parts of the world to attend this past press conference, I was hesitant to create a huge disturbance by combating what was being said and for that I am truly sorry.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/25206972/floyd-mayweather-says-never-agreed-official-fight-kickboxer|title=Mayweather pulls back on announced Japan fight|work=ESPN.com|access-date=November 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2018, Mayweather confirmed that a three-round [[Exhibition fight|exhibition boxing match]] against Nasukawa would indeed happen after the initial misunderstanding had been resolved.<ref>{{cite web |title=Floyd Mayweather: Retired boxer agrees to face kickboxer Tenshin Nasukawa |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/46242977 |website=BBCSport.com |date=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Floyd Mayweather vs Tenshin Nasukawa fight 'back on' |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11556252/floyd-mayweather-vs-tenshin-nasukawa-fight-back-on |website=SkySports.com |language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nThe fight took place at the [[Saitama Super Arena]] in [[Japan]] on December 31 and ended on a TKO in the first round, when Nasukawa's corner waved off the fight after he had been knocked down three times.<ref>{{cite news |title=American wins farcical Tokyo fight over distraught kickboxer\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/floyd-mayweather-tenshin-nasukwa-flight-result-tokyo-a8705636.html\n|publisher=[[The Independent]]\n|date=December 31, 2018\n|access-date=January 1, 2019|author=Jack Watson|language=en-UK}}</ref> After the fight, Mayweather clarified that he is still retired and only did the fight to entertain fans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayweather: \"I'm still retired\" |url=https://www.boxingnews24.com/2019/01/mayweather-im-still-retired/ |website=BoxingNews24.com |access-date=January 4, 2019 |date=January 1, 2019}}</ref> The match and its ending, however, were controversial, and drew condemnation and accusations of match-fixing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.scmp.com/sport/boxing/article/2180408/floyd-mayweather-v-tenshin-nasukawa-fake-rigged-or-not-farcical-fight|title=Floyd Mayweather v Tenshin Nasukawa \u2018fake\u2019? Rigged or not, farcical fight spits in face of fans|date=January 2, 2019|author=Nicolas Atkin|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/combat-sports/boxing/1009700/twitter-accuses-floyd-mayweather-of-fixing-fight-against-tenshin-nasukawa/amp/|title=Twitter accuses Floyd Mayweather of fixing fight against Tenshin Nasukawa|date=January 1, 2019|author=|publisher=Fox Sports Asia}}</ref> Mayweather reportedly earned $9 million for the fight.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mazique |first1=Brian |title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. Makes The Easiest $9 Million Of His Career At Rizin 14 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brianmazique/2018/12/31/floyd-mayweather-jr-makes-the-easiest-9-million-of-his-career-at-rizin-14/#4ea0b99c55f4 |website=Forbes.com |access-date=January 4, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Entertainment career==\n\n===WWE===\n[[File:Mayweather.jpg|thumb|upright|Mayweather during his brief tenure in the [[WWE]]|alt=Mayweather, wearing sunglasses, white T-shirt and chains, in wrestling ring with red ropes]]\nMayweather appeared at [[WWE]]'s [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out]] pay-per-view event on February 17, 2008, in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. He was involved in a [[kayfabe|storyline]] altercation with [[Big Show]] when Mayweather jumped a security barricade and attacked Big Show to help [[Rey Mysterio Jr.|Rey Mysterio]], whom Show had threatened to [[chokeslam]]. Mayweather originally assumed a [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]] role in the story lines, which met with some resistance from fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/exclusives/showtimeinvegas|accessdate=February 19, 2008|title=Showtime in Vegas|last=Difino|first=Lennie|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=February 17, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080225164002/http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/exclusives/showtimeinvegas <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 25, 2008}}</ref> The attack resulted in Big Show receiving a broken nose. The following night on ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', Big Show challenged Mayweather to a one-on-one [[No Disqualification match]] at [[WrestleMania XXIV]], which Mayweather accepted. At WrestleMania, Mayweather defeated Big Show in a knockout with [[brass knuckles]] to maintain his unbeaten record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/matches/6464482/results/|title=Mayweather defeats Big Show|accessdate=March 30, 2008|publisher=WWE |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080402210221/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/matches/6464482/results/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 2, 2008}}</ref> Mayweather was reportedly paid $20&nbsp;million for the fight.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=3264690 \"Mayweather to make $20 million as part of WrestleMania XXIV\"]. (February 26, 2008). ''[[ESPN]]''. Retrieved August 10, 2015.</ref> 1 million PPV buys were reported for WrestleMania XXIV, grossing $23.8 million in revenue.\n\nMayweather was guest host for ''Raw'' in Las Vegas on August 24, 2009. He interfered with a tag-team match, which resulted in a loss for the Big Show (again a [[heel (professional wrestling)|heel]]) and his partner [[Chris Jericho]] as Mayweather gave [[Montel Vontavious Porter|MVP]] brass knuckles to knock Jericho out, giving MVP and his new tag-team partner [[Mark Henry]] the win and a shot at the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|Unified WWE Tag Team Titles]] at [[WWE Breaking Point]] against [[Jeri-Show]]. He then celebrated with Henry and MVP, turning face. Later that night, he was involved in a backstage segment with [[Vince McMahon]], [[D-Generation X]], and [[Carly Col\u00f3n|Carlito]], helping McMahon prepare for his six-man tag team match against [[The Legacy (professional wrestling)|The Legacy]] and DX. During the segment, McMahon knocked out Carlito.\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\nMayweather appeared on the [[Dancing with the Stars (American season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''; his partner was Ukrainian-American professional ballroom dancer [[Karina Smirnoff]]. On October 16, 2007, Smirnoff and Mayweather were the fourth couple to be eliminated from the competition, finishing in ninth place.<ref>[http://realitytvworld.com/news/floyd-mayweather-jr-karina-smirnoff-cut-from-dancing-with-stars-5934.php Floyd Mayweather Jr., Karina Smirnoff cut from 'Dancing with the Stars']. Realitytvworld.com (October 17, 2007). Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMayweather resides in a {{convert|22000|sqft|adj=on}}, five-bedroom, seven-bath, custom-built mansion in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204423804574286344148657298 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 17, 2009 |first= Hannah|last= Karp|title=Floyd Mayweather's Hideout }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Mayweather recorded a rap song titled \"Yep\" that he used for his entrance on [[WrestleMania XXIV]] in his match against [[Big Show]].\n\nMayweather owns a boxing gym called the \"Mayweather Boxing Club\" located in the Chinatown Plaza in Las Vegas.\n\nIn 2011, Mayweather paid for the funeral of former super lightweight world champion and former opponent [[Genaro Hernandez]], who died of cancer after a three-year battle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dan-rafael/post/_/id/52/floyd-mayweather-shows-generous-side-genaro-hernandez-family-boxing |title=Mayweather quietly shows generous side \u2013 Dan Rafael Blog |publisher=ESPN |date=June 15, 2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Domestic violence and battery convictions===\nIn 2002, Mayweather was charged with two counts of domestic violence and one count of misdemeanor battery. He received a six-month suspended sentence and two days of house arrest and was ordered to perform 48 hours of community service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/30/sports/plus-boxing-suspended-sentence-for-mayweather.html |title=Suspended Sentence For Mayweather |work=The New York Times |date=March 30, 2002 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Mayweather was given a one-year suspended jail sentence, ordered to undergo counseling for \"impulse control\" and pay a $1,000 fine (or perform 100 hours of community service) after being convicted of two counts of misdemeanor battery against two women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=1820745 |title=Mayweather gets suspended sentence \u2013 boxing |publisher=ESPN |date=June 12, 2004 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Mayweather pleaded no contest to a misdemeanor battery charge after hitting and kicking a bouncer, receiving a 90-day suspended jail sentence.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hoffer, Richard |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1105325/index.htm |title=This Saturday night, the ultratalented Floyd Mayweather \u2013 06.27.05 \u2013 SI Vault |work=Sports Illustrated |date=June 27, 2005 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=5551166 Las Vegas police seek Floyd Mayweather Jr. for questioning in domestic battery case \u2013 ESPN]. Sports.espn.go.com (September 9, 2010). Retrieved on June 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2010, it was reported that Mayweather was being sought by police for questioning after his former girlfriend, Josie Harris, filed a domestic battery report against him. Harris accused Mayweather of battery in the past, but those charges were dropped in July 2005 after Harris testified that she had lied and that Mayweather had not battered her.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Mayweather was taken into custody September 10, 2010, but was released after posting $3,000 bail. Mayweather was initially charged with felony theft (stemming from the disappearance of Harris's mobile phone); on September 16 two felony coercion charges, one felony robbery charge, one misdemeanor domestic-battery charge and three misdemeanor harassment charges were added.\n\nOn December 21, 2011, a judge sentenced Mayweather to serve 90 days in the county jail for battery upon Harris in September 2010. Mayweather reached a deal with prosecutors in which he pleaded guilty to [[misdemeanor]] [[battery (crime)|battery]] in exchange for prosecutors dropping the felony battery charge. Mayweather also pleaded no contest to two counts of misdemeanor [[harassment]], stemming from threats to his children. In addition to the 90-day sentence Mayweather was ordered to complete 100 hours of [[community service]], a 12-month domestic-violence program and to pay a fine of $2,500.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jail time for Mayweather after guilty plea|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-12-21/news/30544534_1_leonard-ellerbe-josie-harris-officer-bill-cassell|newspaper=NY Daily News | location=New York|date=December 21, 2011}}</ref> On June 1, Mayweather began serving his county jail sentence,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ritter|first=Ken|title=Boxer Mayweather due to begin Vegas jail sentence|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/boxer-mayweather-due-begin-vegas-182523834--box.html|accessdate=June 1, 2012|newspaper=Yahoo|date=June 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603101815/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/boxer-mayweather-due-begin-vegas-182523834--box.html|archivedate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> and was released on August 3, 2012.\n\n===Sued for defamation===\nIn May 2015, following his bout against Pacquiao, Josie Harris sued Mayweather for $20 million for defamation, claiming that Mayweather lied during an interview with Katie Couric in April. During that interview, he called her a drug abuser while discussing the 2010 domestic-violence incident which ended up with Mayweather going to jail for two months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/after-fight-of-the-century-mayweather-pacquiao-both-sued/ |title=After 'Fight of the Century,' Mayweather, Pacquiao both sued |website=BusinessMirror.com |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The case remains pending {{as of|2017|September|19|lc=y|df=US}}.<ref>[https://www.lacourt.org/casesummary/ui/ Los Angeles Superior Court online docket search]; Case No. PC056372.</ref>\n\n===Stripped of WBO welterweight title===\nOn Monday, July 6, 2015, Mayweather was stripped of his WBO Welterweight Champion (147 lbs) title for noncompliance with the regulations of the organization. Mayweather won the WBO Welterweight title when he beat Manny Pacquiao in the May 2 bout. However, the WBO rules say that boxers cannot hold world titles in multiple weight classes, and Mayweather already held two junior middleweight championship titles when he won the welterweight title.\n\nMayweather had until 4:30&nbsp;p.m. EST on July 3 to vacate the two other belts and pay a $200,000 sanctioning fee. He did not comply, and the WBO vacated the title on July 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brow, Jason |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2015/07/07/floyd-mayweather-stripped-title-wbo-welterweight-championship/ |title=Floyd Mayweather Stripped Of Title: WBO Vacates Welterweight Championship |publisher=[[Hollywood Life]] |date=July 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 SEC settlement ===\nIn November 2018, together with [[DJ Khaled]], Mayweather agreed to a total settlement of $750,000 with the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) for failing to disclose payments accepted from issuers of initial coin offerings, including a personal $100,000 promotional payment from beleaguered cryptocurrency firm [[Centra Tech]] Inc.,<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/mayweather-dj-khaled-settle-over-digital-coin-promotions/2018/11/29/2e111ac6-f433-11e8-99c2-cfca6fcf610c_story.html|title=Mayweather, DJ Khaled settle over digital coin promotions|last=Gordon|first=Marcy|date=November 29, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> whose co-founders were indicted for fraud in May 2018. According to the SEC, \"they are its first cases involving charges for violating rules on touting investments in so-called initial coin offerings, or ICOs.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post\"/>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|ko-wins=27\n|dec-wins=23\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|50\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|50\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Conor McGregor]]\n|TKO\n|10 (12), {{small|1:05}}\n|[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Conor McGregor|Aug 26, 2017]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[T-Mobile Arena]], Paradise, Nevada, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|49\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|49\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Andre Berto]]\n|UD\n|12\n|[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Andre Berto|Sep 12, 2015]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;